1. c4 c5 {Welcome to our course "1.c4 c5 for Black". This is part of the "Full Repertoire for Black" series, continuing from the previously published courses "QGA for Black" and "Jobava London Reversed." Against the 1.c4 English, we recommend 1...c5, a fascinating continuation that allows you to play for the full point. Unlike 1...e5, which is commonly analyzed and essentially a reversed Sicilian, 1...c5 has received far less attention from authors. While 1...e5 is a solid move, it can be tricky to handle if you lack experience with the Sicilian Defense as White (1.e4 c5). In contrast, 1...c5 is a highly practical and versatile choice, suitable for players of all styles.} 2. Nc3 {In the English Opening, there are many possible move orders, but in this introduction, we will focus on a single move order that leads to all the analyzed positions.} (2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {White doesn't have anything better than 5.Nc3 or 5.g3, and both of them lead to different chapters that we cover in the database.}) 2... Nc6 3. Nf3 ({White can also play without Nf3:} 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. a3 $5 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gb2b4] a3-Rb1-b4 plan will be analyzed in Chapter 12.} (5. e3 {[%cal Gg1e2] White's idea is Nge2. We will discuss it in Chapter 13.}) (5. e4 {The Botvinnik system will be analyzed in Chapter 14.}) (5. d3 {and other hybrid lines will be studied in Chapter 15.})) 3... Nf6 4. g3 (4. d4 {This is a very concrete move, and here it's important to be well-prepared.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 e6 6. g3 {is White's main line and the most theoretical one. In our opinion, this is the most important and difficult Chapter in the database. Once you learn it, all the rest will be much easier. We will speak about it in Chapter 1.} (6. a3 {Will be analyzed in Chapter 2.}) (6. e4 {Will be analyzed in Chapter 3.}) (6. Ndb5 {Will be analyzed in Chapter 4.}) (6. Bf4 {and other sidelines will be analyzed in Chapter 5.})) (4. e4 {Is rare, but we will analyze it in Chapter 9.}) (4. e3 {Will be analyzed in Chapters 10 and 11.}) 4... g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 {This is the starting position of the Symmetrical Fianchetto.} 6. d4 (6. O-O d6 7. d4 (7. d3 {will be analyzed in Chapter 6, together with other White's sidelines at move 7.}) 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 {will be analyzed in Chapter 7.}) 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 {Now, our recommendation will be the fresh} h5 $5 {and we will study it in Chapter 8. This line became popular only in the last 2 years, and it is frequently used with success by GM Sindarov.} *

