{[%evp 0,26,22,-6,15,11,15,15,8,8,12,19,19,6,6,13,29,30,28,28,28,29,29,19,5,-12,0,13,20]} 1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 (3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. a3 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gb2b4] This move has been played in more than 5.000 games, and it was GM Dvirnyy's recommendation. White's idea is to organize a quick queenside counterplay by playing Rb1-b4.} (5. e3 {[%cal Gg1e2,Ge1g1,Gd2d4] e3-Nge2 is known as "Fischer set-up". White's idea is to play d4, but Black will also be in time to play d5, after which a lot of exchanges are usually following. That's why this line is considered very drawish.} e6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d5] We copy White's development, and this is considered the most reliable set-up for Black.} 6. Nge2 Nge7 7. O-O O-O 8. d4 {This is White's standard continuation, and the idea of the "Fischer set-up".} cxd4 {White can now choose if to recapture with the pawn or with the knight.} 9. Nxd4 (9. exd4 d5 10. cxd5 Nxd5 $11) 9... d5 {[%csl Rc1] Better to dealy the exchange on d4. Why? Because White will not be able to activate his bishop on c1 for a few more moves.} 10. cxd5 (10. Nxc6 $6 {Is a positional mistake.} bxc6 $15 {[%csl Gc6,Gd5,Rg2,Gg7][%cal Yg7a1,Rg2d5] Black is already preferable. Our bishop on g7 is much stronger than White's one on g2. For example:}) 10... Nxd5 11. Nxd5 exd5 $11 {[%cal Yc6d4] Very likely, we will take on d4 one day, reaching a symmetrical and drawish position. But if White is not careful, we might also not take on d4!}) (5. e4 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gg1e2,Ge1g1] The Botvinnik system is a variation with a very long history. White's idea is to develop with Nge2-00-d3, and then try to play h3-Be3 with d4 ideas, or sometimes f4. Nowadays, it's not so popular anymore. First of all, even if White manges to develop his pieces in a desired way, this doesn't cause any problem to the Black color. Secondly, as we will see, it's very difficult for White to achieve his ideal set-up.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] This is a very strong move. Our idea is to play b7-b5 quickly.} 6. a4 {[%cal Gb7b5,Rb2b4] This is White's best move. However, the inclusion of a6-a4 means that White will never be able to play for b2-b4, while Black can play for b7-b5.} (6. Nge2 {it's White's standard move, but we are ready for the immediate} b5 $1 7. cxb5 $6 {Capturing the pawn is critical but not good:} axb5 8. Nxb5 Ba6 9. Nec3 Bxc3 $1 {We give-up our strong bishop for concrete reasons.} 10. Nxc3 Nb4 $36 {[%cal Gb4d3]}) 6... d6 7. d3 {Now, Black has a choice: we can develop the knight on f6 or on e7. I prefer it on e7, but objectively, both moves are fine.} e6 {This is my recommendation. I prefer to have the knight on e7 for two reasons: our bishop g7 will still have a strong influence on the diagonal, and we will always have the option to play f7-f5. I repeat myself: I don't want to say that e6-Nge7 is better than Nf6; this is just my personal preference.} 8. Nge2 Nge7 9. O-O O-O 10. Rb1 {[%csl Gb1][%cal Yc1e3,Yc6d4,Gb2b4] This is a standard-useful move for White. The idea is to continue with Be3, and when we will play Nd4, White will have b2-b4 ideas.} ({Whenever White plays} 10. f4 {we can at least play} f5 $132) ({Whenever White plays} 10. Be3 {[%cal Gd3d4] with the idea d4, we can block it by playing} Nd4 $132) 10... Bd7 $1 {The most precise continuation, in my opinion.} (10... Rb8 $6 {Is not so accurate because it allows White to execute his idea:} 11. Be3 Nd4 {[%csl Gb1]} 12. b4 $1 $14) 11. Be3 Qa5 $1 {This is a strong prophylactic move against d4.} (11... Nd4 $6 12. b4 $14) 12. d4 {White's idea.} ({if White plays a waiting move like} 12. h3 {then we can already play} Nd4 $132 {[%csl Ga5][%cal Ge7c6,Rb2b4,Ya5b4] Because White doesn't have the b2-b4 idea. Our plan will be to play Nec6 next, and then we can retreat the queen to a more standard square like c7.}) 12... cxd4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 {the simplest solution} 14. Bxd4 Bxa4 $1 {[%csl Rd4] key move.} 15. Nxa4 Bxd4 16. Qxd4 Qxa4 17. Qxd6 Nc6 $11 {[%csl Gc6,Rg2] Objectively, our position is absolutely fine, but in practice, it might be even easier to play it from the Black's side because White's bishop on g2 could be less strong than our knight.}) 5... Nf6 {This is my recommendation. For the moment, we want to complete our development.} 6. Rb1 O-O {We still ignore b2-b4.} 7. b4 {Now, Black is fine in more than one way, but I like the following one:} cxb4 8. axb4 a5 $5 {White needs to make an important decision on the queenside.} 9. bxa5 $1 (9. b5 $6 {This move may look logical, but it's a mistake:} Nb4 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gd7d5] Our knight on b4 supports d7-d5.}) 9... Rxa5 10. d3 {White delays Nf3 with the idea of not allowing d7-d5, but...} (10. Nf3 $6 {allows} d5 $1 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 $15 {[%csl Gb7] Equal material, but we have the b7 pawn, which gives us nice hopes for the future.}) 10... d5 $1 {We can play it anyway!} 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Rxd5 13. Bxd5 Qxd5 $44 {Pawn down, but we have a very nice compensation. For example:} 14. Nf3 Bc3+ 15. Bd2 Bxd2+ 16. Qxd2 Nd4 $15) 3... Nf6 4. g3 (4. e3 {White prepares d2-d4.} e5 {This is my recommendation.} 5. d4 {White's most common continuation, but also 5.Be2 deserves serious attention.} e4 {[%csl Rc1] I recommend playing e4 now, without exchanging on d4, so that White's bishop on c1 cannot be developed for the moment.} 6. Ne5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Rc5d4] If White wants to move his knight, then this is the best square for it. Remember: unlike in the previous two examples, if White plays Ne5, we do not exchange on d4.} (6. d5 {White wants to enter in an endgame:} exf3 7. dxc6 dxc6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. gxf3 {In practice, White scored 53%, but this happened mostly because Black players did not fully understand how to play. In my opinion, if we know the key ideas, the endgame is just equal.} g6 {[%cal Gf8g7] First step: we develop our bishop on the strong h8-a1 diagonal.} 10. b3 {This is White's logical continuation because he wants to contest our bishop.} Bg7 11. Bb2 {Now we have a choice that occurs also in the Berlin endgame: where to place our king? e7 or c7? In my opinion, both ideas are fine, but I will suggest playing with the king on c7.} b6 12. O-O-O+ Kc7 {This is my recommendation.}) 6... g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8] We want to play Bg7-00. We will analyze this position separately in the next Chapter 11.} (6... cxd4 $2 7. exd4 g6 8. Bg5 $1) 7. g4 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf1g2,Gg4g5] This is the most critical move, in my opinion. White's ideas are g5 or Bg2, playing against our e4 pawn.} (7. Be2 {most logical move, but not dangerous for us:} Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. b3 $6 {most common move, but after} Ne7 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gh7h5,Gd7d6] White has problems with Ne5.}) 7... h6 $1 {[%cal Rg4g5] We have to stop g5.} 8. Bg2 Bg7 9. h3 {[%csl Yg4] White's best. h3 is a useful move to defend g4.} (9. h4 {[%cal Gg4g5] White's idea is g5.} d5 $1) 9... Qe7 {My recommendation.} 10. b3 $1 {critical and it was played in the game Mamedyarov-MVL, 2018.} (10. Nxc6 $6 dxc6 11. O-O $4 {Sharma-Gabrialian, 2018.} g5 $3 $19 {[%cal Gh6h5] h5 next and Black is winning.}) 10... O-O $5 $146 {my recommendation.} (10... Nxe5 $2 {it's a bad idea to accept the pawn:} 11. dxe5 Qxe5 12. Bb2 $16 {White has a lot of ideas on the a1-h8 diagonal and against our e4 pawn.}) 11. O-O (11. Bb2 {not so precise:} cxd4 12. exd4 d6 13. Nxc6 bxc6 {[%cal Gd6d5] we are ready to play d5.} 14. d5 (14. O-O $2 d5 $17) 14... Bb7 $36) 11... d6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 $13) (4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e6 6. g3 {This is White's main line and the most concrete and big line of this database. Ensure you have studied it well before going to the following chapters.} (6. a3 {The second most played move in the position, the idea is to prevent ...Bb4.} Bc5 $5 {is a very interesting move, and my recommendation.} 7. Nb3 {is the best and the most played.} Bb6 8. c5 {The main line, and the idea of Nb3.} Bc7 9. g3 {is the main line, and the only serious try.} O-O 10. Bg2 b6 {is our idea, so let's do it now.} 11. O-O Be5 {[%csl Ge5] The position is playable for both sides, with equal chances, but Black scored 46% which means a better score than White in this position.}) (6. e4 Bc5 $5 {My recommendation. It's 30 times less played than the mainline 6...Bb4, but we can get more interesting positions, in my opinion.} 7. Nc2 $1 {[%csl Yc2][%cal Gc1e3] This is White's most critical continuation, but it has been played in less than 20 games. The idea is that Nc2 prepares Be3.} (7. Nxc6 {White's most common continuation, but it's harmless.} dxc6 $1 {With the bishop on b4, dxc6 is not good, but here it works very well:} 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {[%cal Ge6e5]}) (7. Nb3 Bb4 {[%csl Rb3] only now, we play Bb4 when White's knight is on b3, and the Nxc6 option is no longer available for him.} 8. Bd3 {We can decide now if to equalize or play an interesting position:} O-O $5 {fighting option.} 9. O-O Ne5 $1 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Ge5g6] our knight will go to g6.}) 7... Qb6 $1 {[%csl Yb2][%cal Rc1e3,Gb6b2] We prevent Be3.} (7... O-O 8. Be3 $14 {Nothing dramatic, but White is definitely slightly better.}) 8. Qd2 $1 {[%cal Gc3a4] the strongest because it prepares Na4, and Black will not have checks on the e1-a5 diagonal.} Ng4 {I recommend to go for the most principled line.} 9. f3 $1 {Now starts a concrete sequence.} (9. Nd1 $6 O-O 10. h3 Nf6 $36 {[%cal Gd7d5] d5 next.}) 9... Nf2 10. Na4 Qc7 11. Nxc5 Nxh1 {[%csl Rh1] We have an extra exchange, but of course, White has a good compensation. Still, I think that this position is very interesting, and we have chances to play for three results.}) (6. Ndb5 {A concrete line. Very often, White will emerge with an extra pawn in the endgame, but Black will always have significant compensation and, in some cases, even the initiative or an advantage. I have analyzed this line deeply to ensure 100% certainty that Black always has sufficient compensation and that White lacks any meaningful practical tries.} d5 $1 7. Bf4 {Mainline.} (7. cxd5 {This is, of course, the first thing that we should check.} Nxd5 8. Nxd5 exd5 9. Qxd5 {White can immediately win a pawn.} Bb4+ 10. Bd2 {Now, it's an important moment.} Be6 $1 {We are not afraid of the endgame.} 11. Qxd8+ Rxd8 12. Nc3 O-O $44) 7... e5 {The next three moves are forced:} 8. cxd5 exf4 9. dxc6 bxc6 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {This is the starting position of the 7.Bf4 variation.} 11. Rd1+ $1 {[%csl Ge1,Yf2][%cal Ye1f2] White's king should stay on e1 to protect f2.} (11. O-O-O+ $6 {[%csl Yc1,Rf2] would be nice, but with the king on c1 White will have concrete problems with f2:}) 11... Bd7 12. Nd6 {[%csl Rb2] Now, we have more than one good continuation, and you can choose according to your style.}) 6... Qb6 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yd4f3,Yd4c2,Ye2e3]} 7. Nb3 {[%csl Rc4] White's most common continuation, and it's as critical as 7.Ndb5, which is the mainline in this file.} (7. Ndb5 {the most concrete line.} Ne5 $1 {[%csl Rc4,Rf2][%cal Gb6c6,Gf6g4] Important move. We attack c4, prepare Qc6 or Nfg4.} (7... Bc5 $2 {would be a mistake for concrete reasons:} 8. Bg2 $1 Bxf2+ 9. Kf1 $18) 8. Bg2 (8. Bf4 $5 {a line that you should know very well.} Nfg4 $1 {key move; without it, our position is just lost.} 9. e3 {main move.} a6 10. h3 {mainline.} axb5 11. hxg4 Nxc4 12. Qb3 $1 {White can force equality.} d5 13. Bxc4 dxc4 14. Qxb5+ Qxb5 15. Nxb5 {equal with many moves, for example:} Ra5 16. Nd6+ Bxd6 17. Bxd6 e5 $11 {[%csl Rg4]}) 8... a6 {The last important crossword of this Chapter.} 9. Qa4 {mainline.} (9. Na4 Qd8 10. Nd6+ Bxd6 11. Qxd6 Nxc4 {[%csl Rf8][%cal Gd6c5,Gc5b4,Re8g8]} 12. Qc5 d5 13. b3 Bd7 $1 {[%cal Ga8c8] important move.} 14. bxc4 Bxa4 {White is not worse but also not better:}) 9... Rb8 10. Na3 $1 {the modern direction.} (10. Be3 $6 {old mainline, but dubious:} Bc5 11. Bxc5 Qxc5 12. Qa3 b6 $1 13. Nd6+ Ke7 14. Qxc5 bxc5 15. Nxc8+ Rhxc8 16. b3 g5 $36 {Black gets a fantastic endgame.}) 10... Bxa3 {the most concrete way.} 11. Qxa3 Nxc4 12. Qb3 {White has compensation, but no more:} Qxb3 {safest.} 13. axb3 Ne5 14. Bf4 d6 15. O-O-O Ke7 $11 {[%cal Gh8d8] if we play Rd8 White is worse.}) 7... Ne5 $1 {[%csl Rc4,Rh1][%cal Gb6c6] immediate counterplay against c4 and in addition we have Qc6 idea.} 8. e4 {[%cal Gf2f4] White is ready to push f4-e5.} (8. Bg2 $5 {Dubov likes this continuation. White sacrifices a pawn and has a typical-Catalan compensation.} Nxc4 {we have to capture the pawn.} 9. O-O Be7 10. e4 {[%cal Gd1e2]} d6 {[%cal Ye4e5] very important move to stop e4-e5.} 11. Qe2 Qa6 $1 {[%cal Gc8d7,Ye8g8] The best in my opinion. The key thing to understand is that almost always Bd7 will be our next move.} 12. Rd1 Bd7 $1 {also now it's important to start with Bd7.} (12... O-O $2 13. e5 dxe5 14. Nd2 $18) 13. Bf1 (13. e5 dxe5 14. Nd2 Rc8 $15 {[%csl Gc8]}) 13... Rc8 14. Rd4 Ne5 $1 15. Qxa6 bxa6 $36 {Objectively White is not worse, but he will need to play accurate moves to hold equality.}) 8... Bb4 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4] very important move because we create the Nxe4 threat and stop for a moment f4-e5.} 9. Qe2 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ge4e5] mainline. White defends e4 and is ready to push f4-e5.} (9. f4 $4 Nxe4 $19) (9. c5 $5 {Interesting direction.} Bxc5 10. Nxc5 Qxc5 11. Be3 {White plays for the two bishops and for the activity.} Qb4 12. Qb3 Nf3+ $1 (12... Qxb3 13. axb3 $36 {[%cal Gc3b5] some concrete problems like Nb5.}) 13. Kd1 Qd6+ 14. Kc1 {[%cal Yf1g2,Yf3e5,Gf2f4] White's idea is Bg2-Ne5-f4. That's why we have to play a strong prophylactic move.} Ne5 $1 $146 {[%csl Ge5,Rh1]}) 9... d6 {very complicated position from a strategic perspective, I suggest to concentrate on the most important things.} 10. Bd2 {[%cal Ge1c1] White is ready for long castle, and I recommend} (10. Bg2 $6 {natural, but White has concrete problems with c4:} Qc7 $1 {[%csl Rc4] we somehow force Nd2, which is not good for White:}) (10. f4 {old line, already solved from many years:} Nc6 11. Be3 Bxc3+ $1 12. bxc3 Qc7 13. Bg2 e5 $1 {[%cal Rb3d4,Gb7b6] very important positional move. Also we stop Nd4.}) 10... a5 $5 {and to follow the high-quality game Sevian-Dominguez, 2024.} 11. f4 {engine's top choice.} (11. Bg2 {not critical:} a4) (11. O-O-O {also not critical:} a4 12. Na1 Bc5 13. f3 Bd7 $36 {[%cal Ge5c6,Gc6d4,Ya4a3] Balanced position, but Black has many ideas and easy play.}) 11... Nc6 12. Be3 Qd8 {[%cal Ga5a4,Ge6e5] Black has two main ideas: a4 and e5.} 13. Bg2 {natural but not precise:} e5 $1 {[%csl Rg4] we get the important g4 square for the knight.}) 4... g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. d4 {If White starts with d4 immediately, we don't have time for d7-d6.} (6. O-O {The main issue with castling first is that Black can play d6.} d6 {And Black is in time to develop the bishop to d7, to support c6.} 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 {[%csl Gd6,Gd7,Yh8][%cal Gc6d4,Ge8g8,Ga7a6,Gb7b5,Ga8b8,Yh7h5,Yh5h4] We are in time comparing to 6.d4. Black's position is very flexible, because Black didn't castle yet. This means that we can either play the normal plan of 0-0-Nxd4-Bc6 or Rb8-a6-b5, but we have the alternative plan of h5-h4, because the rook is still on h8.}) 6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 h5 $5 {This is our recommendation. We follow the last trends of young strong GMs. The biggest expert of this line is GM Sindarov.} (7... O-O 8. O-O d6 {is anyway a good move here, but it is not the same, because we sacrifice the pawns on c6. This is not our recommendation.} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bxc6 Rb8 {Black needs to study a lot of lines just to make a draw. I think you can achieve if you do a good job, but you are playing for one result: only for a draw.}) 8. h3 {[%cal Rh5h4,Gg3g4] White positionally stops h4 because if 8...h4 now, after 9.g4 White is better.} (8. Nxc6 $6 dxc6 $1 {we should welcome the endgame.} 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 $36 {[%csl Rc4,Gc6,Rg2,Gh5][%cal Gh5h4,Gg7a1] h5 is very useful move also in the endgame.}) (8. O-O {allows} h4 9. c5 {the most critical move in my opinion.} hxg3 10. hxg3 Rh5 $1 {[%csl Rc5] important move to target c5.} 11. Nb3 {White defends c5 and now we need to play 2 other precise moves:} d5 $1 12. cxd6 Bh3 $1 (12... exd6 $6 13. Bf4 $14) 13. Bxh3 Rxh3 {We are fine, for example:}) (8. h4 {[%csl Rh4,Gh5] h5-h4 inclusion is good for Black because we have the g4 square:} Ng4 $1 {[%csl Gg4]}) 8... Nxd4 $1 ({Don't start with} 8... O-O $6 {because after} 9. Be3 $1 $14 {[%csl Gh3,Rh5][%cal Rf6g4] This is the only case where h5-h3 is convenient for White because we don't have Ng4.}) 9. Qxd4 {Difficult to say if it's better to start with d6 or with 00.} O-O {I prefer to start with 9...00, but it doesn't mean that it's the best.} 10. O-O d6 {[%csl Gh2,Gh7] Doesn't matter if we start with 9...d6 or 9...00, White can always get this position if he wants. Compared to the big main line, the inclusion of h5-h3 favors Black, in my opinion.} 11. Qd3 {White's most common and natural move.} Be6 {[%csl Rh3,Gh5][%cal Gd8c8] Compared to the big mainline where the pawns are on h2 and h7, here we have the Qc8 strong resource, and h3 is often hanging.} 12. Nd5 (12. Bd2 $2 {Would be a mistake now because of} Qc8 $17 {[%csl Rc4,Rh3][%cal Ge6h3,Ge6c4]}) (12. Kh2 {White defends h3, but spends an important tempo:} Rc8 13. b3 d5 $1 $17) (12. b3 {allows} d5 $1 {which is not necessary, but it immediately equalizes:}) 12... Nxd5 13. cxd5 Bd7 $132 {[%csl Gd7,Gg7][%cal Gd8b6] typical good structure.} *

