{[%evp 0,44,25,-25,14,8,17,15,11,11,11,11,11,13,-2,-7,14,-36,-54,-3,0,-49,-21,-42,-64,-64,27,20,20,21,27,31,31,24,50,50,54,54,46,40,52,52,52,54,55,16,16]} 1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e6 6. g3 {This is White's main line and the most concrete and big line of this database. Ensure you have studied it well before going to the following chapters.} Qb6 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Yd4f3,Yd4c2,Ye2e3]} 7. Ndb5 {the most concrete line.} (7. e3 {too passive:} Bb4 8. Bg2 Ne5 {[%csl Rc4] typical counterplay against c4.} 9. O-O (9. Qe2 $6 Qc5 $15 {[%csl Rc4]}) 9... Nxc4 10. Na4 Qa5 11. a3 {White starts with a3 not to allow b3-Na3.} (11. b3 Na3 $132 {[%csl Ga3][%cal Gd7d5,Gc8d7]}) 11... Be7 12. b3 {[%cal Rc4a3]} Ne5 13. Bb2 Ng6 $132 {playable and no problems for Black.}) (7. Nc2 $6 {[%csl Rc2]} Bc5 {[%csl Rc2] Nc2 is bad.} 8. e3 d5 $1 {[%csl Rc2]} 9. cxd5 (9. Bg2 dxc4 $15) 9... exd5 {[%csl Rc2]} 10. Bg2 Bg4 $1 $15) (7. Nf3 {also harmless:} d5 8. cxd5 (8. Bg2 dxc4 9. O-O {David-Karthik, 2020.} Bd7 $132 {Bd7 is very useful move for us.}) 8... exd5 9. Bg2 (9. Nxd5 $4 {huge mistake.} Nxd5 10. Qxd5 Be6 $19 {[%cal Gc6b4] Nb4 or Bb4. We have too many threats.}) 9... d4 10. Na4 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 Qb5 {very good version of the Tarrasch structure:} 12. O-O Bxd2 13. Nxd2 O-O 14. Rc1 Bg4 $11 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ga8d8] Svidler-Vidit, 2020.}) (7. Nb3 {[%csl Rc4] White's most common continuation, and it's as critical as 7.Ndb5, which is the mainline in this file.} Ne5 $1 {[%csl Rc4,Rh1][%cal Gb6c6] immediate counterplay against c4 and in addition we have Qc6 idea.} 8. e4 {[%cal Gf2f4] White is ready to push f4-e5.} (8. Bg2 $5 {Dubov likes this continuation. White sacrifices a pawn and has a typical-Catalan compensation.} Nxc4 {we have to capture the pawn.} 9. O-O Be7 10. e4 {[%cal Gd1e2]} d6 {[%cal Ye4e5] very important move to stop e4-e5.} 11. Qe2 Qa6 $1 {[%cal Gc8d7,Ye8g8] The best in my opinion. The key thing to understand is that almost always Bd7 will be our next move.} 12. Rd1 (12. Nd4 Bd7 $1 {always important to start with Bd7 and not with 00.} (12... O-O 13. b3 Ne5 14. Qxa6 bxa6 15. f4 Ng6 16. Nc6 $36 {[%csl Gc6] Full compensation for White, and maybe some initiative.}) 13. b3 Ne5 14. Qxa6 bxa6 $132 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Ga8c8,Ge8g8,Rd4c6] White doesn't have Nc6 now, for example:} 15. f4 Nd3 16. Rd1 (16. e5 $2 dxe5 17. Bxa8 Bc5 $17) 16... Nxc1 17. e5 {engine move, but White doesn't equalize even here:} (17. Raxc1 Rc8 $15) 17... dxe5 18. fxe5 Rc8 19. exf6 Rxc3 20. fxe7 e5 $1 $36 {strong important move.}) (12. e5 dxe5 13. Rd1 (13. Nd2 $2 Nxd2 14. Qxa6 bxa6 $19 {[%csl Rf1] very important detail is thar Rf1 is hanging.}) 13... Bd7 $1 {extremely important to start with Bd7.} (13... O-O $4 14. Nd2 $18) 14. Nd2 Rc8 15. Bxb7 Qxb7 16. Nxc4 O-O 17. Nxe5 Be8 $15 {[%cal Gf6d7,Ge7b4]}) 12... Bd7 $1 {also now it's important to start with Bd7.} (12... O-O $2 13. e5 dxe5 14. Nd2 $18) 13. Bf1 (13. e5 dxe5 14. Nd2 Rc8 $15 {[%csl Gc8]}) 13... Rc8 14. Rd4 Ne5 $1 15. Qxa6 bxa6 $36 {Objectively White is not worse, but he will need to play accurate moves to hold equality.}) 8... Bb4 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4] very important move because we create the Nxe4 threat and stop for a moment f4-e5.} 9. Qe2 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ge4e5] mainline. White defends e4 and is ready to push f4-e5.} (9. f4 $4 Nxe4 $19) (9. c5 $5 {Interesting direction.} Bxc5 (9... Qc6 {also possible, but I don't recommend it because at least White can force a draw.} 10. Bg2 (10. f3 $5 {White can also get a complicated game} b6 11. Bf4 Ng6 12. Bd6 bxc5 13. a3 Bxc3+ 14. bxc3 a5 $1 $13 {a5 only move, but the position is still very unclear.}) 10... Qb5 11. Bf1 Qc6 $11 {we cannot avoid the repetition.}) 10. Nxc5 Qxc5 11. Be3 {White plays for the two bishops and for the activity.} Qb4 12. Qb3 Nf3+ $1 (12... Qxb3 13. axb3 $36 {[%cal Gc3b5] some concrete problems like Nb5.}) 13. Kd1 Qd6+ 14. Kc1 {[%cal Yf1g2,Yf3e5,Gf2f4] White's idea is Bg2-Ne5-f4. That's why we have to play a strong prophylactic move.} Ne5 $1 $146 {[%csl Ge5]} (14... O-O 15. Bg2 Ne5 16. f4 Nd3+ 17. Kb1 $16) (14... a6 $4 15. Bg2 Ne5 16. f4 $1 $18) 15. f4 (15. Bg2 Neg4 $17) 15... Neg4 16. Bg1 (16. e5 $2 {[%csl Rf1]} Qc6 $1 $19 {[%csl Gc6,Rh1][%cal Gc6h1] we win an important tempo against White's rook.}) 16... b6 $1 17. h3 $1 {only move.} (17. Bg2 $2 Bb7 18. e5 Qc7 $17) (17. e5 $2 Qc6 $19) 17... Bb7 $1 {only move.} (17... Nh6 $2 18. Rh2 $16) 18. hxg4 Nxe4 19. Rh2 Nxg3 $13 {A new unclear position, evaluated with the classical "0.00" by the engine, but we are in new territory from already many moves.}) 9... d6 {very complicated position from a strategic perspective, I suggest to concentrate on the most important things.} 10. Bd2 {[%cal Ge1c1] White is ready for long castle, and I recommend} (10. Bg2 $6 {natural, but White has concrete problems with c4:} Qc7 $1 {[%csl Rc4] we somehow force Nd2, which is not good for White:} 11. Nd2 Bd7 {[%cal Ga8c8]} 12. f4 (12. O-O Rc8 $17 {[%csl Rc4]}) 12... Ng6 {[%csl Gg6]} 13. O-O O-O $15 {[%csl Rd2] White's Nd2 is bad.}) (10. f4 {old line, already solved from many years:} Nc6 11. Be3 (11. Bg2 $2 e5 $1 $17) (11. Bd2 O-O 12. O-O-O e5 13. f5 {[%cal Gg3g4,Gg4g5]} Nd4 $15) 11... Bxc3+ $1 (11... Qc7 12. Bd2 $13 {[%csl Gb6,Rc7] White gets a better version of 11.Bd2, because Qc7 stays worse than Qb6.}) 12. bxc3 Qc7 13. Bg2 e5 $1 {[%cal Rb3d4] very important positional move. Also we stop Nd4.} 14. c5 $1 {White has to play it, otherwise we play b6 and fix White's bad structure.} (14. f5 $2 b6 $17 {[%cal Gc8a6,Gf6d7]}) (14. O-O $6 b6 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6,Gf6d7,Ga8c8] we don't rush with short castle because White could play then f5-g4-g5 with some chances for attack.} (14... O-O $2 15. f5 $16 {[%cal Gg3g4,Gg4g5]}) 15. f5 Ba6 $17 {[%csl Ge7][%cal Ge8e7] maybe our king will just go to e7.}) 14... b6 15. cxd6 Qxd6 16. O-O O-O $11 {Good position. You can check the game Radjabov-Gelfand, 2013.}) 10... a5 $5 {and to follow the high-quality game Sevian-Dominguez, 2024.} 11. f4 {engine's top choice.} (11. Bg2 {not critical:} a4 12. Nb5 Bxd2+ 13. Nxd2 O-O 14. f4 Nxc4 $1 {not necessary, but the best.} 15. Nxc4 (15. Qxc4 $2 Ng4 16. Qe2 Ne3 $17) 15... Qxb5 16. Nxd6 Qb4+ 17. Qd2 Qb6 18. e5 Nd5 $13) (11. O-O-O {also not critical:} a4 12. Na1 Bc5 13. f3 Bd7 $36 {[%cal Ge5c6,Gc6d4,Ya4a3] Balanced position, but Black has many ideas and easy play.}) 11... Nc6 12. Be3 Qd8 {[%cal Ga5a4,Ge6e5] Black has two main ideas: a4 and e5.} 13. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Ra5a4] strong prophylactic move against a4.} (13. Bg2 {natural but not precise:} e5 $1 {[%csl Rg4] we get the important g4 square for the knight.} 14. O-O (14. a3 Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 Ng4 $15) ({White doesn't have time to play} 14. h3 $2 a4 15. Nc1 a3 $17 {[%cal Gf6h5,Ge2h5,Ga3b2]}) 14... a4 15. Nc1 Ng4 $15) 13... O-O $1 ({White's idea is} 13... a4 14. a3 Bxc3 15. bxc3 $13) (13... e5 {White gets a better version of the 13.Bg2 line after} 14. a3 Bxc3 15. bxc3 Ng4 16. f5 $1 Nxe3 17. Qxe3 $14 {[%cal Gc4c5] c5 next.}) 14. a3 {the best, according to the engine.} (14. Bg2 $6 e5 $1 {[%cal Gf6g4] same story as 13.Bg2.} 15. h3 (15. O-O Ng4 $15) 15... Nd4 16. Qd3 Ne6 $36 {[%cal Ge6c5] Nc5 next, and Black's position is slightly preferable.}) 14... Bxc3 15. bxc3 b6 16. Bg2 Qc7 17. O-O Ba6 $132 {Dominguez showed a very good preparation, and Black's position was not worse and maybe more interesting in Sevian-Dominguez, 2024.}) 7... Ne5 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Rf2][%cal Gb6c6,Ge5g4,Gf6g4] Important move. We attack c4, prepare Qc6 or Nfg4.} (7... Bc5 $2 {would be a mistake for concrete reasons:} 8. Bg2 $1 Bxf2+ 9. Kf1 $18) (7... d5 {second normal option, but less clear than 7...Ne5.}) 8. Bg2 (8. Bf4 $5 {a line that you should know very well.} Nfg4 $1 {key move; without it, our position is just lost.} (8... d6 $2 {natural but a huge mistake:} 9. Bg2 a6 10. Qa4 $1 $16 {Huge advantage for White.}) 9. e3 {main move.} (9. Qa4 $5 {Engine-style try. Interesting, but very dangerous also for White.} Qxf2+ 10. Kd2 $1 (10. Kd1 $2 {we can see that king on d1 is bad in the following variation:} Kd8 11. h3 Ne3+ $19 {[%csl Rd1]}) 10... g5 {the best to fight for the advantage. White's play is absolutely forced for the next moves.} (10... Kd8 $2 11. h3 $18) (10... Qc5 {also possible.} 11. Ne4 Qb4+ 12. Qxb4 Bxb4+ 13. Kc2 Nxc4 $1 $13) 11. Nc7+ (11. Bxg5 $4 Nf3+ $19) 11... Kd8 12. Bxe5 Qe3+ {only one e-mail game here.} 13. Kc2 Qxe5 14. Nxa8 Ne3+ 15. Kb3 $1 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gb3a2] White's idea is a3-Ka2.} (15. Kc1 $4 Bc5 $19) 15... Bc5 16. a3 $1 {[%cal Gb3a2]} Ke7 17. Ka2 d5 $1 18. Qa5 $1 {if not Qa5 White is worse.} dxc4 19. Bh3 Bd7 {of course, we are going very far, but it's interesting to see how everything should end, according to the engine.} 20. Rad1 Rxa8 21. Nd5+ exd5 22. Qxc5+ Ke8 23. Bxd7+ Kxd7 24. Qb5+ Ke6 25. Qxb7 Rb8 26. Qa6+ Qd6 27. Qxa7 (27. Qxd6+ Kxd6 $19 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Gf7f5,Gd6e5,Ge5e4] Ke5-f5 next. Black is winning.}) 27... Nxd1 28. Rxd1 Qb6 29. Qxb6+ Rxb6 $36 {[%cal Gb6b3] Now White can make a draw with precise play:} 30. b4 $1 cxb3+ 31. Kb2 $11 {[%cal Ga3a4] 'a' pawn provides enough counterplay for a draw.}) 9... a6 10. h3 {mainline.} (10. Nc7+ $6 {would be a mistake because of} Qxc7 11. Qxg4 Qxc4 $1 12. Bxc4 (12. Qd1 $2 Qc6 $17) 12... Nxg4 $15 {just extra pawn.}) (10. Qa4 {possible move, but Black has a lot of good continuations:} Ra7 {White must find 11.h3 only move.} (10... g5 $5 {might be the easiest:} 11. Bxe5 Nxe5 12. O-O-O Rb8 13. Nd4 Bg7 $13) 11. h3 $1 {only move.} (11. Be2 $2 axb5 12. Qxb5 Qc6 $19) (11. Nxa7 $2 Qxb2 12. Be2 Qxc3+ 13. Kf1 Qxa1+ 14. Kg2 Qb2 15. Qd1 Qb6 16. Nxc8 Qc6+ $19 {Noe-Gschnitzer, 2018.}) 11... axb5 12. Qxb5 Qc6 (12... Qxb5 13. Nxb5 Bb4+ {also fine.}) 13. hxg4 Nd3+ 14. Bxd3 Qxh1+ 15. Bf1 Qc6 $13 {Unclear position for three results, evaluated with "0.00" by the engine.}) 10... axb5 (10... Qc6 $5 {is another way.}) 11. hxg4 Nxc4 (11... Qc6 $5) 12. Qb3 $1 {White can force equality.} (12. Rc1 $6 d5 13. b3 Bb4 14. bxc4 Ra3 15. Be5 Qa5 $36) 12... d5 13. Bxc4 dxc4 14. Qxb5+ Qxb5 15. Nxb5 {equal with many moves, for example:} Ra5 16. Nd6+ Bxd6 17. Bxd6 e5 $11 {[%csl Rg4]} 18. g5 (18. f3 $6 e4 $36) 18... Bg4 $11 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Ge8d7,Gd7e6,Gh7h5]}) 8... a6 {The last important crossword of this Chapter.} (8... Nxc4 {possible, but White has a lot of ideas, for example:} 9. b3 $5 {not the main move, but it has some venom.} a6 10. bxc4 axb5 11. Nxb5 Bb4+ 12. Bd2 Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2 O-O 14. Rb1 $36 {or 14.00 and then Rfb1. Very close to equal, but White can play a risk-free and slightly more pleasant game.}) 9. Qa4 {mainline.} (9. Be3 $6 Qa5 $15 {[%csl Re3][%cal Ge5c4,Yc4e3] Nxc4 idea becomes stronger.}) (9. Na3 $6 {dubious but Black needs to find the best reaction.} Bxa3 $1 10. bxa3 Nxc4 11. O-O d5 $15 {White doesn't have full compensation for the pawn.}) (9. Na4 Qd8 (9... Qa5+ {possible but I don't like it:} 10. Nbc3 Nxc4 11. O-O d5 12. b3 Na3 13. Bb2 $44 {[%cal Ge2e4] White has very good compensation and a lot of ideas.}) 10. Nd6+ (10. Nbc3 {White's only idea is to force a repetition after} Nxc4 11. b3 Ne5 12. Be3 (12. Bf4 $6 d6 $15) 12... d5 13. Bb6 Qd6 14. Bc5 Qd8 $11) 10... Bxd6 11. Qxd6 Nxc4 {[%csl Rf8][%cal Gd6c5,Gc5b4,Re8g8]} 12. Qc5 (12. Qb4 $6 {less precise than 12.Qc5 because Black can include the move a6-a5:} d5 13. b3 a5 $1 14. Qc5 Nd6 15. Nb6 Ra6 $1 $17 {key difference between 12.Qb4 and 12.Qc5.}) 12... d5 13. b3 Bd7 $1 {[%cal Ga8c8] important move.} (13... Nd6 $6 14. Nb6 $14) 14. bxc4 Bxa4 {White is not worse but also not better:} 15. cxd5 {most common move.} (15. Qa3 {Black has a lot of good continuations.} b5 $5 {might be the simplest.} (15... Qd7 {also possible.} 16. Bb2 dxc4 17. O-O Bc6 18. Rfd1 Qc8 $13) 16. cxb5 axb5 17. Bf4 b4 18. Qxb4 Qa5 $11) 15... Nxd5 16. O-O Qd7 $1 {[%cal Ga8c8] We prepare Rc8.} 17. Ba3 (17. e4 Rc8 18. Qd4 Nf6 19. Qb4 Qb5 20. Qa3 Rc4 $11 {[%cal Yb5b4,Yb5c5,Ge8g8] Qc5 or Qb4 next, and we will castle.}) 17... Rc8 18. Qd4 f6 $1 $132 {[%cal Ge8f7,Ga4b5,Yc8c4,Gd5c3] We can continue with Nc3, Kf7 or Bb5 and Rc4 next. It depends on White's next move.}) 9... Rb8 10. Na3 $1 {the modern direction.} (10. Be3 $6 {old mainline, but dubious:} Bc5 11. Bxc5 Qxc5 12. Qa3 b6 $1 13. Nd6+ Ke7 14. Qxc5 bxc5 15. Nxc8+ Rhxc8 16. b3 g5 $36 {Black gets a fantastic endgame.}) 10... Bxa3 {the most concrete way.} (10... Be7 {also possible.} 11. O-O O-O 12. Bf4 d6 13. b4 Qc7 14. Rac1 Ng6 15. Be3 Bd7 $132 {just playable position.}) 11. Qxa3 Nxc4 12. Qb3 {White has compensation, but no more:} Qxb3 {safest.} (12... Qc7 {possible, but I am not 100% sure about it. For example, if we follow some engine's moves for both sides:} 13. Qb4 b5 14. b3 Bb7 15. Bxb7 Qxb7 16. O-O Ne5 17. Bf4 Nc6 18. Qd6 Rc8 19. Rac1 h5 $13 {This position is evaluated "0.00" by the engine, but it doesn't look clear to me.}) 13. axb3 Ne5 14. Bf4 d6 15. O-O-O Ke7 {[%cal Gh8d8] if we play Rd8 White is worse.} 16. Rxd6 $1 {necessary move.} Ng6 $1 {[%cal Gg6f4]} (16... Kxd6 $6 17. Rd1+ Ke7 18. Bxe5 Ra8 19. Bd6+ Ke8 {White can play for domination with many moves:} 20. b4 $36) 17. Rd8 $1 {important move.} (17. Rd2 $6 {White shouldn't allow Nxf4.} Nxf4 18. gxf4 b5 19. Rhd1 Bb7 $15 {[%csl Rb2,Rb3,Rf2,Rf4,Rh2][%cal Gh7h6,Gg7g5,Yf4g5,Yh6g5] we will play against White's structure.}) (17. Rhd1 $4 {just a blunder:} Nxf4 18. gxf4 Nd5 $19 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ge7d6]}) 17... Rxd8 18. Bxb8 Bd7 19. Ba7 Rc8 $1 {[%cal Gd7c6] we prepare Bc6. 20.Bxb7 is not possible because of Rc7.} (19... Bc6 $6 20. Bxc6 bxc6 21. Kc2 $16 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Gh1a1] Ra1 next, and White can play against the a6 pawn.}) 20. Kb1 Bc6 21. e4 Nd7 22. Be3 f5 $5 $11 {[%cal Gd7f6,Yg6e5] White has two bishops, but it doesn't mean anything here. We can continue with Nf6 and Nge5.} *

