{[%evp 0,23,28,-12,16,16,16,11,4,3,0,0,0,-1,8,8,13,12,3,7,7,10,10,10,27,-15]} 1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e6 6. a3 {The second most played move in the position, the idea is to prevent ...Bb4.} Bc5 $5 {is a very interesting move, and my recommendation.} (6... Be7 {is also good, but you need to study} 7. e4 {We will see a similar position, but here the moves a3-Be7 are included.} O-O {which is still quite good for Black, for example:} 8. Nf3 {is usually played.} Qa5 $5 {For more precision, you can try this move.} (8... Qc7 {The main line.} 9. Be2 b6 10. O-O Bb7 11. Re1 $132 {[%cal Ge2f1] Useful move, White can be tiny slightly better, but of course, it's a position for 3 results, playable.}) 9. Bd2 $5 {is the critical move.} (9. Bd3 {If White finishes development,} d5 {is the idea, Black is doing absolutely fine. For example, in the game Gelfand-Erigaisi:} 10. O-O dxc4 $5 {is the easiest, I believe.} (10... d4 $6 {was played in the game, but I don't like.} 11. Na4 $1 $146 {is unpleasant.} (11. Ne2 {is also playable.} e5 12. b4 $1 {Important move, now White plays for compensation.} Bxb4 13. axb4 Qxa1 14. Qb3 Qa6 {But the position is fine also for Black.} 15. b5 Qb6 16. c5 Na5 17. Qa3 Qc7 18. Bd2 b6 {White has full compensation, but no advantage.} 19. Rc1 Be6 $13 {Although, Black should know some tricky things.}) 11... e5 12. b4 Qc7 13. c5 $36 {The position is tough to play for Black.}) 11. Bxc4 Rd8 12. Qe2 {White's idea is e5, that's why Black should play} Ne5 $1 {And the position is fine for Black.} (12... Bd7 $6 {is too slow.} 13. b4 $16 {[%cal Ge4e5] Followed by e5, this is better for White.}) 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14. g3 Bd7 15. Bf4 Qh5 $11) 9... Qh5 {is the best, and there are around 30 high level games here.} 10. Be2 d5 $1 {Necessary and strong.} 11. cxd5 exd5 12. exd5 Nxd5 {White has some small ideas, but it should be very close to equality.} 13. Nd4 Qe5 14. Nxc6 bxc6 {White is very slightly symbolically better.} 15. Nxd5 Qxd5 16. O-O Bf6 $11 {But it is of course, very close to equal. So to conclude, 6...Be7 is a very good move to equalize. But also you can get a complicated game with Qc7.}) 7. Nb3 {is the best and the most played.} (7. Be3 {is a very rare move, and one idea to keep in mind is} Be7 $5 $11 {[%csl Re3][%cal Re2e4,Gd7d5] White can't push e4, and d5 comes next with an absolutely fine position.}) (7. e3 {This consolidates the knight, but it is a bit passive.} O-O 8. Be2 (8. b4 $2 {is a bad move, because Black can} Bxd4 9. exd4 d5 $1 {That's quite important.} 10. c5 (10. Be3 dxc4 11. Bxc4 b6 $15 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ga8c8] Now we are playing against the isolated pawn, but we have a very good version.}) 10... e5 $1 {We are in time to create more than counterplay, this is advantage.} 11. dxe5 Qe7 12. f4 Nxe5 $1 {is the point.} 13. fxe5 $4 Qxe5+ 14. Kd2 d4 $19 {White can resign.}) 8... d5 {And it is important to understand that:} 9. cxd5 exd5 {[%csl Gd5] This version of the isolated pawn is fantastic for Black. We are not playing for equality, but for more.} 10. O-O Re8 11. Nf3 {is the most common, to not allow taking on d4.} (11. b4 Bb6 12. Nf3 d4 {is even stronger.} 13. exd4 Nxd4 {We have an extra tempo compared to what we have seen.} 14. Nxd4 Qxd4 {[%csl Re2] White cannot take on d4.} 15. Bb2 Qh4 $36 {Huge initiative.}) 11... a6 12. b4 Ba7 (12... d4 $11 {is good for equality.}) 13. Bb2 d4 {You can play now d4, and it is absolutely fine.} 14. exd4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Bxd4 16. Bf3 {Black can play as he wishes, but one interesting idea is} Bf5 $5 {With the point that} 17. Bxb7 {can be met with} Ng4 $1 {And it is White who needs to show precision:} 18. Bf3 $1 (18. Bxa8 $4 {is just lost for White.} Qh4 $19 {f2 falls and it's game over.}) 18... Nxh2 19. Kxh2 Qh4+ 20. Kg1 Rad8 {And the only move is} 21. Nd5 $1 Bxb2 $36 {But you can regain the piece and it is risk free.}) 7... Bb6 8. c5 {The main line, and the idea of Nb3.} (8. Bf4 {Now Black cannot play anymore with d6.} d5 9. c5 {is the best.} (9. e3 {If White just develops, we do the same.} O-O 10. Be2 Qe7 {[%cal Gf8d8] Rd8 next.} 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 exd5 {If White doesn't take on d5, Rd8-d4 is our plan.} 13. Qxd5 {If White takes, we have more than compensation:} Rd8 14. Qg5 Qe4 15. O-O Qc2 $15 {We will regain material, and the position is unpleasant for White.}) 9... Bc7 10. Bxc7 Qxc7 11. Nb5 {This is an important concrete position.} Qe5 $1 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Ge5b2] is my recommendation, to attack the b2 pawn.} (11... Qe7 {was seen in the game Gelfand-Gorshtein, European Club Cup 2024, but I think White is slighlty better.} 12. Nd6+ Kf8 13. e3 b6 14. Nxc8 Rxc8 15. Rc1 $14 {And Gelfand won the game.}) 12. Nd6+ Ke7 {So now White has no time for e3.} 13. Qc1 $1 {[%cal Gf2f4] is necessary, protects the b2 pawn and prepares f4.} (13. e3 $4 {is just lost.} Qxb2 14. Be2 Qc3+ 15. Kf1 Rd8 $19 {Clear extra pawn.}) 13... g5 $5 {[%cal Rf2f4] Many good moves exist, but I like this one, to prevent f4.} (13... Rd8 {is also fine, but White has easier play.} 14. e3 (14. f4 Qh5 15. e3 Qg6 $11) 14... Ne4 15. f4 Qh5 16. Nxe4 dxe4 {This structure can be tricky.} 17. Qc2 e5 $1 $11 {You need to find.}) 14. e3 b6 $146 {Concrete move, to undermine the knight, and I think White is risking more.} (14... Bd7 $6 {was seen in Martinez-Karthik, 2020.} 15. Bb5 $1 $14 {White can take on c6 and consolidate.}) 15. Bb5 {is the only move that makes sense, and now} (15. Be2 $2 {makes no sense.} bxc5 16. Nxc8+ Rhxc8 17. Qxc5+ Qd6 $15 {Better endgame for Black.}) 15... Nb8 $5 {We go back, it's a bit strange, but bxc5 is the idea.} 16. Be2 $1 {Engine shows this as the best, but it's very strange play.} (16. O-O {Logical, but already risky for White.} bxc5 17. Nxc8+ Rxc8 18. Nxc5 a6 19. Ba4 {To protect against Nd7.} Ne4 20. Nd3 Rxc1 21. Nxe5 Rc7 22. Rfc1 Raa7 $36 {Black is preferable.}) 16... bxc5 17. Nb5 $1 {is the idea.} c4 {And yes, the position is quite complicated.} 18. N3d4 (18. f4 gxf4 19. exf4 Qe4 20. Qc3 Na6 $13 {Same story here, Black is pawn up, but complicated and 0.00.}) 18... Bd7 19. a4 Ne4 $13 {New position, complicated fight, but 0.00.}) (8. e4 {Playable move, Black has a choice.} d6 (8... d5 {is also possible.} 9. exd5 exd5 10. cxd5 (10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. cxd5 O-O $1 {And it's very important that White cannot take on c6.} 12. Be2 (12. dxc6 $4 {loses the queen.} Bxf2+ $1 $19) 12... Qh4 $1 {Tempo on f2.} 13. O-O Rd8 $36 {[%cal Gc8e6] Some initiative for Black.}) 10... Ng4 {Concrete line.} 11. Be3 (11. Qe2+ $2 {is just bad.} Ne7 {and anyways Be3 is necessary.} 12. Be3 Nxe3 13. fxe3 O-O {But Black is better in more than one way.} 14. O-O-O Nf5 $15 {[%cal Gf5e3]}) 11... Bxe3 {is also fine for Black.} 12. fxe3 Nxe3 {I checked some lines just to be sure.} 13. Qd3 (13. Qd2 {If this, Black can} Nxf1 {With tempo.} 14. Rxf1 Ne5 15. O-O-O O-O 16. h3 Qb6 $11 {This is of course great.}) 13... O-O {is more precise.} (13... Nxf1 14. Qe4+ $5 {Maybe White has this extra idea.}) 14. dxc6 Qb6 15. Nd4 {Only good move.} Re8 $1 16. Ne4 $1 {Necessary to defend against the discovery.} Qxb2 17. Rb1 Nxg2+ 18. Kd1 $1 {Necessary.} Ne3+ 19. Ke1 {At minimum, Black has a draw.} Nc2+ $5 {or maybe you can play for something more.} 20. Qxc2 Qxd4 21. Rb4 Qe5 $11 {Still equal, but White is risking more.}) 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O e5 $132 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gc8e6,Ya7a5,Ya5a4] Black is at least fine here.}) (8. g3 {is harmless, because after} d5 9. cxd5 exd5 {[%csl Ra3,Rb3] In a Tarrasch type of position, one strange move means equal, two strange moves means advantage for Black.} 10. Bg2 d4 11. Na4 O-O 12. O-O Re8 $36 {[%cal Gc8g4] Absolutely fine for Black.}) 8... Bc7 9. g3 {is the main line, and the only serious try.} (9. Bg5 {was tried in some games, but I don't understand it.} h6 10. Bh4 b6 {And Black is doing great.} 11. e3 Be5 $36 {[%cal Rc5b6,Ga7b6] was the game Cuenca-Macias Pino, Madrid 2024. Black went on to win.}) (9. e4 {I can understand, but not a scary move.} b6 10. Be3 (10. cxb6 {is not great, both recaptures are fine.} axb6 {But if you don't want to allow anything, this is always a good recapture.} (10... Bxb6 {is also fine, don't be scared to allow a bishop on d6.} 11. Bf4 O-O 12. Bd6 Ne7 $15 {[%eval -20,0] for Black.}) 11. Bd3 O-O 12. O-O Ne5 $15 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Ge5g6] Black is doing fantastic.}) 10... O-O 11. Be2 {was the game Moroni-Oparin, 2017. Black continued with 11...Rb8, but I think} bxc5 $146 {was more precise.} 12. Nxc5 (12. Bxc5 {leads to the same.} d6 13. Be3 Bb6 $36) 12... d6 13. Nb3 Bb6 $36 {Black is just doing fanastic here. So we can say that e4 is a harmless idea.}) (9. Nb5 {Don't be afraid to give the pair of bishops.} O-O 10. Nxc7 Qxc7 11. g3 Rd8 $5 {Also interesting.} (11... b6 {To fight for the long diagonal.} 12. Bg2 Bb7 13. O-O Ne5 $11 {Black is doing great.}) 12. Bg2 d6 {is the point, and Black is preferable.} 13. cxd6 Rxd6 14. Qc2 e5 15. O-O Be6 {[%cal Rb3c5,Gc6d4] Despite not having the pair of bishops, our pieces are excellent.} 16. Be3 {it the best to prevent Nd4.} Rc8 17. Rac1 b6 18. Nd2 Qd8 19. Qb1 h6 {The position can be maximum equal for White.} 20. Ne4 Nxe4 21. Bxe4 Nd4 $11 {It is not a scary pair of bishops.}) 9... O-O 10. Bg2 b6 {is our idea, so let's do it now.} 11. O-O (11. Nb5 Be5 {transposes.} (11... bxc5 $5 {is an extra option.} 12. Nxc7 Qxc7 13. Nxc5 d6 {Not clear where to put the knight.} 14. Na4 {The best probably, to go to c3 later.} Bb7 15. O-O Na5 $11 {We get rid of the pair of bishops, and Black's position is fine.})) 11... Be5 {[%csl Ge5] The position is playable for both sides, with equal chances, but Black scored 46% which means a better score than White in this position.} 12. a4 {is maybe the best move.} (12. Be3 {is one of White's best tries.} Ba6 {[%cal Rd1d3] To stop Qd3.} (12... Ng4 13. Qd3 {Engine says +0.15, but it's difficult to believe.}) 13. Nd4 (13. Rc1 Ng4 14. Qd2 {is not the same.} Bc4 $1 {[%csl Rb3]} 15. Na1 Nxe3 16. Qxe3 Bd4 $17 {So you see, quite easy to get worse with White.}) 13... Ng4 $1 {leads to absolute equality.} 14. Nxc6 dxc6 15. Qc1 {is necessary.} Nxe3 16. Qxe3 Bd4 $11 {Just nothing for White.}) (12. Bf4 {was played in the game Moroni-Wei, but the problem with this move is that after} Bxf4 13. Bxc6 {That's why Moroni decided to equalize.} (13. gxf4 $6 {can be structurally dangerous for White.} Bb7 $36) 13... dxc6 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. gxf4 Ba6 $11 {And this was absolute equality.}) (12. Qd3 {You don't need to remember move by move, just playable position.} Rb8 13. Rd1 bxc5 14. Nxc5 Qe7 $11) (12. cxb6 {was played in the game Moroni-Goryachkina.} axb6 13. e4 Ba6 {Black can play for more.} (13... Bb7 $11 {was played in the game, but a bit slow.}) 14. Re1 Bxc3 $1 {Great move.} 15. bxc3 Ne5 $36 {[%csl Rc4,Rd3,Ge5][%cal Gd8c7] Black's position is very beautiful.}) 12... bxc5 {is quite simple.} 13. Nxc5 d5 14. e4 {is the best, and now Black has a lot of moves to equalize.} (14. Nd3 $6 {Nagy-Chow.} Bxc3 $1 {And Black is playing for an advantage.} 15. bxc3 Na5 $15 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gc8a6,Ga8c8]}) 14... Rb8 {is clear equality, in Matlakov-Svidler.} (14... d4 $146 15. Nb5 a6 16. Na3 Nd7 $132 {Very interesting position.}) 15. exd5 exd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 Qxd5 18. Bxd5 Nd4 {The compensation is full.} 19. Be3 Nc2 $5 {was more precise.} (19... Bh3 {was also fine, but White had a small chance.} 20. Bg2 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Nc2 22. Rab1 $146 {But still it's 99% draw.} Nxe3+ 23. fxe3 Rxb2+ 24. Rxb2 Bxb2 25. Rb1 Ba3 26. Nd7 Rd8 $11) 20. Rab1 Nxe3 21. fxe3 Rxb2 $11 *

