{[%evp 0,46,20,0,14,16,19,11,11,17,17,17,22,6,26,-3,-1,8,16,4,3,3,11,3,3,3,28,-62,-35,-11,-11,0,0,0,0,0,8,0,0,8,0,0,22,35,35,35,57,61,61]} 1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e6 6. e4 Bc5 $5 {My recommendation. It's 30 times less played than the mainline 6...Bb4, but we can get more interesting positions, in my opinion.} (6... Bb4 {is the mainline, but after} 7. Nxc6 bxc6 (7... dxc6 $6 {is not good because of} 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. e5 $1 $16 {[%csl Rb4,Gc5] And this is the main difference compared to the 6...Bc5 line.}) 8. Bd3 {White has a pleasant position, for example:} e5 (8... d5 9. exd5 exd5 10. O-O O-O 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Be3 $14 {slightly better and risk-free for White.}) 9. O-O O-O 10. h3 $5 {useful move, this is just an example, but other moves are also possible for White.} d6 (10... Bc5 11. Re1 d6 12. Be3 Bxe3 13. Rxe3 $14) (10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 d6 12. c5 $1 dxc5 13. Qf3 $14 {/= Black can equalize, but White's position is more pleasant and risk-free.}) 11. Na4 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gb2b4] White is ready for a3-b4.} d5 {the best, according to the engine.} 12. exd5 cxd5 13. a3 Bd6 14. cxd5 {now you need to be very well prepared to equalize:} e4 15. Bc2 Ng4 $1 $146 {important move, and it's equal. 6...Bb4 is objectively a good move, but I don't want to play it because White gets a risk-free game, and very often, we need to play extremely accurately just to equalize.}) 7. Nc2 $1 {[%csl Yc2][%cal Gc1e3] This is White's most critical continuation, but it has been played in less than 20 games. The idea is that Nc2 prepares Be3.} (7. Nf3 $4 {let's start with the worst knight's retreat.} Ng4 $1 $19) (7. Ndb5 $2 {second worst option for White.} O-O 8. Nd6 (8. Bf4 d5 $1 9. exd5 exd5 10. cxd5 Ng4 $1 $19) 8... Qb6 $17 {[%csl Rf2]}) (7. Be3 $2 {supporting the knight on d4 is not a good idea:} Qb6 $1 8. Na4 {Now, we have two good continuations:} (8. Nc2 Bxe3 9. Nxe3 Qxb2 $17 {Clean extra pawn.}) 8... Qa5+ $5 {I prefer this direction.} (8... Bb4+ 9. Ke2 {only move.} (9. Nc3 $2 Nxe4 $19) 9... Nxd4+ 10. Bxd4 Qc6 11. f3 Qxc4+ 12. Kf2 Qc7 13. Rc1 Qb8 $15 {White doesn't have full compensation for the pawn.}) 9. Nc3 {only move.} (9. Bd2 $2 Bb4 10. Nxc6 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 Qxa4 $19 {[%cal Gf6e4] Nxe4 next.}) 9... Bxd4 10. Bxd4 e5 11. Be3 Nxe4 $15 {White doesn't have full compensation for the pawn.}) (7. Nxc6 {White's most common continuation, but it's harmless.} dxc6 $1 {With the bishop on b4, dxc6 is not good, but here it works very well:} 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Bf4 {The best because it "prevents" e6-e5.} (9. Bg5 e5 $1 10. O-O-O+ Ke7 $15 {just slightly better for Black.}) (9. e5 $6 Ng4 $15 {[%csl Gc5,Re5,Rf2] With the bishop on b4, White is better, but now he is worse because f2 is also attacked.}) 9... e5 $1 {we can play it anyway, and that's very important.} 10. O-O-O+ (10. Bxe5 $6 Bxf2+ $1 $15 {tactical justification for 9...e5.}) 10... Ke7 11. Bxe5 Ng4 $1 12. Bxg7 {only interesting move for White.} (12. Bg3 $2 Nxf2 $17) 12... Rg8 13. Bd4 Bxd4 14. Rxd4 Nxf2 15. Rg1 {Now, we can decide if to make a draw or continue to play this balanced endgame:} Nh3 (15... Ng4 $5 $132 {[%cal Gg4e5] Ne5 next, looks very playable.}) 16. Rh1 Nf2 $11 {leads to an immediate draw.}) (7. Nb3 Bb4 {[%csl Rb3] only now, we play Bb4 when White's knight is on b3, and the Nxc6 option is no longer available for him.} 8. Bd3 {We can decide now if to equalize or play an interesting position:} (8. Qe2 $6 d6 9. Bd2 {Moroni-Deac, 2025, White's idea is clearly long castle.} O-O $1 10. O-O-O a5 $1 {looks quite unpleasant for White, for example:} 11. a3 Bxc3 12. Bxc3 e5 $1 $15 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gc8e6,Yf6d7,Yd7c5] Qc7-Be6-Nd7-Nc5 next.}) 8... d5 {Very good if you want to equalize:} (8... O-O $5 {fighting option.} 9. O-O Ne5 $1 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Ge5g6] our knight will go to g6.} 10. f4 {critical.} (10. Be2 {most common continuation.} Ng6 $132 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] b6-Bb7 next, it's very playable.}) 10... Qb6+ 11. Kh1 Nxd3 12. Qxd3 d5 $1 13. cxd5 exd5 14. e5 $1 (14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 Re8 $36 {[%cal Gc8d7] Bd7 next, we have two fantastic bishops.}) (14. exd5 Rd8 $36 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gc8e6] Be6 next, and our two bishops will be very strong.}) 14... Bxc3 15. Qxc3 Ne4 $132 {[%cal Gc8f5] Bf5 next, it's a new balanced and interesting position.}) 9. exd5 exd5 10. cxd5 {critical.} (10. O-O {leads to immediate equality:} dxc4 11. Qe2+ (11. Bxc4 O-O $11 {Berkes-Wachinger, 2022.}) 11... Qe7 12. Bxc4 Qxe2 13. Bxe2 O-O $11 {Olsen-Santos, 2024.}) 10... Qxd5 $1 (10... Nxd5 $6 11. O-O $14 {might be unpleasant.}) 11. O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 O-O {White has two bishops, but a worse structure and our pieces are well developed, for example:} 13. c4 Qd7 $1 14. Bb2 (14. Bg5 Rd8 15. Bc2 (15. Bxf6 {trans in 14.Bb2.}) 15... Qxd1 16. Rfxd1 Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Be6 $11) 14... Rd8 15. Bxf6 gxf6 {very important that we are in time to exchange the queens.} 16. Be4 (16. Nc5 $2 Qd4 $1 17. Qh5 Ne5 $17 {[%cal Gg8f8,Gf8e7] Suddenly, White is worse.}) 16... Qxd1 17. Rfxd1 Be6 $11 {Tari-Narayanan, 2023.}) 7... Qb6 $1 {[%csl Yb2][%cal Rc1e3,Gb6b2] We prevent Be3.} (7... O-O 8. Be3 $14 {Nothing dramatic, but White is definitely slightly better.}) 8. Qd2 $1 {[%cal Gc3a4] the strongest because it prepares Na4, and Black will not have checks on the e1-a5 diagonal.} (8. Be3 $2 Bxe3 9. Nxe3 Qxb2 $17) (8. Qe2 $6 O-O {[%cal Gd7d5] we are ready for d5 and use our huge advantage in development.} 9. e5 {only move.} (9. g3 $2 d5 $1 10. e5 Ne4 $19) 9... Ne8 10. g3 $146 {White's only chance is to quickly finish the development.} (10. a3 $6 {Romanov-Koziak, 2011. White's idea is b4, but we can nicely prevent it with} Qb3 $1 $15 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gc5d4] f6 or Bd4 next, and Black is better.}) 10... d6 11. exd6 Nxd6 12. Bg2 {we have many good moves like Nd4, Bd7, but I would start with} Nf5 $5 13. O-O Bd7 $36 {[%cal Rc3a4,Gc6d4] at least equal, but most likely, we have an initiative. Take note that Na4 is not good because of Ncd4!}) 8... Ng4 {I recommend to go for the most principled line.} (8... O-O {safe but sad:} 9. Na4 Bb4 10. Nxb6 Bxd2+ 11. Bxd2 axb6 12. Be3 d5 $36 {Artemiev-Caruana, 2023. The engine will equalize, but over the board, it's easy for White to get some advantage.}) 9. f3 $1 {Now starts a concrete sequence.} (9. Nd1 $6 O-O 10. h3 Nf6 $36 {[%cal Gd7d5] d5 next.}) 9... Nf2 10. Na4 Qc7 11. Nxc5 Nxh1 {[%csl Rh1] We have an extra exchange, but of course, White has a good compensation. Still, I think that this position is very interesting, and we have chances to play for three results.} 12. f4 $1 $146 {[%cal Rc6e5] critical because it stops Ne5.} (12. Qf4 $4 {Carlsen-Erigaisi, 2024.} Qa5+ $1 $19) (12. g3 Ne5 13. Qe3 O-O $36 {[%cal Gd7d5] our idea is to continue with d5.}) 12... O-O 13. Be2 {[%cal Ge1f1] the best, according to the engine. White's idea is to continue with Kf1.} (13. g3 {leads to a complicated game, where White can lose very quickly if he doesn't play well:} d5 14. Bg2 Na5 15. Nb3 Nxc4 16. Qc3 e5 $13) 13... d5 $1 {We already know that this is our standard continuation.} 14. Kf1 dxe4 {there are no games, and it's impossible to analyze this position to the end because both sides have a lot of possible moves and the engine always shows "0.00".} 15. Nxe4 {Let me show you the best lines, according to the engine.} (15. Kg1 e5 $13) 15... Rd8 16. Qe1 e5 $1 {After we play d7-d5, this is our second typical idea to open the position.} 17. Nc3 {[%csl Gd5] Nd5 is the idea.} (17. Ne3 exf4 18. Nd5 Rxd5 $1 19. cxd5 Bf5 $36) 17... Be6 18. f5 $1 {[%csl Gd5] this is how the engine fights for the d5 square.} Bxf5 19. Ne3 Nd4 $1 20. Nxf5 Nxf5 21. Kg1 {[%csl Rh1] At some point, White will eventually take our knight, but he needs to understand the right moment to do it.} (21. Nd5 $6 Qc5 $36) 21... Nd4 {[%cal Gd4c2]} 22. Qf1 Nxe2+ 23. Qxe2 Qd6 24. Be3 $1 (24. Kxh1 $6 {is premature.} Qd3 $15) 24... Qd3 25. Re1 Qxe2 26. Rxe2 Rac8 27. c5 b6 28. Kxh1 bxc5 $11 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gg8f7] f6-Kf7 next, and it's a balanced endgame. In conclusion, I am very fond of the 6.e4 Bc5!? variation and believe the only critical position arises after 7.Nc2, particularly on move 14 following our 13...d5. However, this critical position after 13...d5 has yet to appear in practical play, making it very exciting to follow how the theory will evolve.} *

