{[%evp 0,36,30,-29,11,11,10,12,12,7,9,9,9,6,55,-8,1,-13,-14,-3,10,-1,-8,-14,-14,0,28,27,31,41,50,-63,-58,-45,-24,-24,-39,-50,-50]} 1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e6 6. Ndb5 {A concrete line. Very often, White will emerge with an extra pawn in the endgame, but Black will always have significant compensation and, in some cases, even the initiative or an advantage. I have analyzed this line deeply to ensure 100% certainty that Black always has sufficient compensation and that White lacks any meaningful practical tries.} d5 $1 7. Bf4 {Mainline.} (7. cxd5 {This is, of course, the first thing that we should check.} Nxd5 8. Nxd5 (8. e4 {is harmless:} Nxc3 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Nxc3 {[%cal Gc1e3] If White is in time to play Be3, then he may have a slightly-better endgame, but we can play} Bc5 $1 {[%cal Rc1e3,Gd8e7,Gc8d7,Gh8d8,Ga8c8] and stop White's Be3 development. we will continue next with Ke7-Bd7-Rhd8-Rac8.} 11. Bf4 (11. Bb5 Bd7 $11 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gh8d8,Ga8c8] no problem.}) 11... Ke7 12. Rc1 Rd8 $11 {[%cal Gc8d7,Ga8c8] White doesn't have any tactical idea against Bc5, and we can just continue with Bd7-Rac8.}) 8... exd5 9. Qxd5 {White can immediately win a pawn.} (9. e3 {White tries to play positionally, but we have a fantastic version of the IQP structure:} a6 10. Nd4 (10. Nc3 Be6 $5 {we can play for more than equality.} (10... d4 $11 {immediately equalizes.}) 11. Be2 Bb4 12. Bd2 {White defends against Bxc3 idea, but after} (12. O-O {if White doesn't play Bd2, we will consider Bxc3 at some point, for example:} O-O 13. Bf3 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Rc8 $36 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gc6e5,Ge5c4,Yc6a5] We have good counterplay on the 'c' file and our knight will soon become very strong.}) 12... O-O 13. O-O {[%cal Rd1d2] White is not putting pressure against d5, and we can just play} Qf6 $15 {Then we will put rooks in the center, and our position is preferable.}) 10... Bd6 {[%csl Gd6] Very good square for our bishop.} 11. Be2 O-O {White can now decide which structure he wants to play.} 12. O-O (12. Nxc6 bxc6 {White is not in time to create pressure on the 'c' file.} 13. Bd2 (13. O-O Qf6 $1 $15 {[%csl Rc1] it's difficult for White to develop Bc1.}) 13... Qh4 (13... Qf6 14. Bc3 $132) 14. Bc3 a5 $36 {Very easy play for Black.}) 12... Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Re8 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gd6e5] Be5 next, and we are doing great because it will be difficult for White to develop Bc1. For example:} 14. Rd1 Qc7 15. g3 Be5 16. Qxd5 Be6 17. Qf3 Rad8 $36 {[%csl Rc1] This is more than compensation because our pieces are much more active than White's.}) 9... Bb4+ (9... Qb6 $5 $146 {it's an interesting novelty and it equalizes:} 10. Nc3 (10. Be3 Bb4+ 11. Nc3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Qb2 {it's also fine for us:} 13. Rd1 Qxc3+ 14. Qd2 Qa3 15. g3 O-O 16. Bg2 Be6 $11) 10... Be6 11. Qe4 Bb4 12. e3 Qa5 $44 {Huge compensation, the engine thinks that it will soon end in a draw after something like} 13. Qc2 O-O 14. Be2 Bf5 15. Qb3 Be6 16. Qc2 Bf5 $11 {With a logical moves repetition.}) 10. Bd2 {Now, it's an important moment.} Be6 $1 {We are not afraid of the endgame.} ({Most of players have chosen} 10... Qe7 {with the idea to avoid queens exchange, but I think that here White will be slightly better after} 11. O-O-O Bxd2+ 12. Rxd2 O-O 13. Qd6 $14) 11. Qxd8+ Rxd8 12. Nc3 (12. Bc3 {[%csl Rb5] possible, but White could have future problems with Nb5.} O-O 13. a3 (13. f3 $2 {[%cal Ge1f2] with the idea Kf2, but it's bad.} Bc5 $1 $17) (13. e3 a6 14. Na3 Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 Ne5 $36 {strong initiative.}) 13... Bc5 $1 {[%csl Rb5] Big problems for Nb5.} 14. b4 Bb6 15. e3 (15. a4 {[%cal Yb5a3] computer move, with the idea to give the a3 square for the knight.} a6 16. Na3 a5 17. bxa5 Nxa5 $36 {[%cal Ga5b3] Nb3 next, and it's initiative.}) 15... a6 16. Nd4 Nxd4 17. exd4 {we can take on d4 and equalize, but I think we can play for more with} Bd5 $36 {[%csl Rf1] Not easy to play for White, a human move could be} 18. f3 $6 {but after} Rc8 19. Kd2 Bc7 $1 $17 {[%cal Gc7f4] Bf4 next, and White is much worse.}) 12... O-O 13. e3 (13. O-O-O $6 {[%csl Yc1,Rf2] White would love to play it, but with the king on c1 and not on e1 there are always problems for the f2 pawn.} Ne5 {[%cal Ye5g4,Ye5c4,Yd8c8] Nc4 or Ng4 is our idea.} 14. e3 (14. h3 Rc8 15. Kb1 Nc4 $36) 14... Ng4 $1 15. Be1 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Rxd1+ 17. Kxd1 Rd8+ 18. Kc2 Bxa2 $15) (13. a3 Nd4 $1 {strong intermezzo.} 14. Rc1 Ba5 $36 {I think that here we can play for more than equality.} ({we can immediately force a draw with} 14... Nb3 15. Rd1 Nd4 $11)) 13... Rd6 $146 {I prefer this over Rd7.} (13... Rd7 14. Bb5 {not a problem objectively, but it could be slightly annoying.}) 14. Be2 (14. O-O-O Rfd8 {We will for sure recover the missing pawn:} 15. Be2 (15. Ne4 Bxd2+ 16. Rxd2 Rxd2 17. Nxd2 Rc8 18. Kd1 (18. Kb1 $4 Nb4 $19) 18... Bxa2 $36) 15... Bxa2 16. Nxa2 Bxd2+ 17. Kc2 g6 $11 {Absolutely fine for Black.}) 14... Rfd8 15. Bc1 {engine move, but it cannot be a problem :)} (15. O-O-O Bxa2 $1 $11) (15. Rd1 $2 Bxa2 $1 $17) 15... a6 16. O-O R6d7 {[%cal Yb4e7,Ye7f6] just useful move, and it's not easy for White to play, for example:} 17. h3 (17. f3 $6 {[%csl Re3]} Bc5 18. Kf2 Nb4 $15) (17. a3 Bxc3 18. bxc3 Na5 $44) 17... h6 $44 {What next for White?}) (7. e4 $5 {very rare, but it's not bad for White.} d4 $1 {the simplest solution.} 8. e5 Nxe5 {White will capture on d4 now or later, but the arising positions will be absolutely fine for us.} 9. Qxd4 (9. Bf4 {more engine-style.} Ng6 10. Bc7 Qd7 11. Qxd4 Qxd4 12. Nxd4 Bd7 $11 {[%cal Ga8c8] Rc8 next.}) 9... Qxd4 10. Nxd4 Bd7 11. Be2 Rc8 12. b3 Bc5 13. Nc2 Bc6 $11 {Black cannot be worse.}) 7... e5 {The next three moves are forced:} (7... d4 {is interesting, but objectively White should be better in the following line:} 8. Nc7+ Ke7 9. N3b5 $1 Rb8 10. e3 g5 11. Bd6+ Kd7 12. c5 $1 $146 {strong novelty.} Bxd6 13. cxd6 Ne4 14. Nxd4 Nxd6 15. Ncb5 Ke7 16. Nc3 $14 {Of course it's playable, but White has some, at least small, advantage.}) 8. cxd5 (8. Bg5 $6 {White shouldn't avoid the mainline.} a6 9. cxd5 axb5 10. dxc6 bxc6 $15) 8... exf4 9. dxc6 bxc6 10. Qxd8+ (10. Nd4 $4 Qb6 $19 {[%csl Rb2,Rf1][%cal Gf8b4]}) 10... Kxd8 {This is the starting position of the 7.Bf4 variation.} 11. Rd1+ $1 {[%csl Ge1,Yf2][%cal Ye1f2] White's king should stay on e1 to protect f2.} (11. O-O-O+ $6 {[%csl Yc1,Rf2] would be nice, but with the king on c1 White will have concrete problems with f2:} Ke7 $1 (11... Bd7 12. Nd6 $1 Bxd6 13. Rxd6 $132) 12. Nd4 (12. Nd6 Be6 $17 {[%csl Rd6,Rf1]}) 12... Bd7 13. g3 (13. h3 g6 $15 {[%cal Gf8h6]}) 13... fxg3 14. hxg3 {With the king on e1, White would be better, but here he is much worse because of} Ng4 $1 $17 {[%csl Rf2] For this reason, 11.000 is a mistake.}) (11. Nd4 {solid move, but it doesn't fight for the advantage:} Bd7 12. g3 fxg3 13. hxg3 Bb4 {Black is doing fine. I can mention two classical games:} 14. Bh3 {probably better than Bg2.} (14. Bg2 Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 Kc7 16. O-O Rab8 $36 {Timman-Gligoric, 1984.}) 14... Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 h5 $11 {Shariyazdanov-Sax, 2000.}) 11... Bd7 (11... Ke7 $6 {now this is not so good:} 12. Nd4 Bd7 13. g3 $14 {[%csl Ge1,Yf2][%cal Ye1f2] Compared to the 11.000 line, now White's king is on e1, which means that we don't have Ng4 ideas.}) 12. Nd6 {[%csl Rb2] Now, we have more than one good continuation, and you can choose according to your style.} (12. Nd4 Kc7 $15 {[%csl Gd7,Gf8] White shouldn't play slowly because we can be better with the two bishops in the long term.}) 12... Kc7 {This is my favorite one, but the other two ways are also good.} (12... Bxd6 {safest way.} 13. Rxd6 Ke7 14. Rd4 (14. Rd2 Nd5 15. Nxd5+ cxd5 16. g3 Rhc8 $44) 14... Nd5 15. Nxd5+ cxd5 {Rac8 next, and White is not well-developed to fight for the advantage:} 16. Rxf4 (16. Rxd5 Rhc8 17. Kd2 Be6 $40) (16. g3 Rhc8 17. Bg2 Rc2 18. Bxd5 Rd8 19. O-O fxg3 20. hxg3 Rxb2 $11) 16... Rhc8 17. Kd2 Rab8 18. b3 Rc5 $132) (12... Rb8 $5 {Even this creative way is objectively fine, for example:} 13. Nxf7+ Kc7 14. Nxh8 Rxb2 {[%cal Gf8b4] Our idea is Bb4.} 15. Rb1 (15. g3 $4 Bb4 16. Rc1 Ne4 $19 {shows White's problems.}) (15. Rc1 Bb4 16. Kd1 c5 {[%cal Gd7a4] we have Ba4+ idea.} 17. Rc2 Bxc3 18. Rxc3 Rb1+ 19. Kc2 (19. Rc1 $4 Ba4+ 20. Kd2 Ne4+ $19) 19... Bf5+ 20. Rd3 Rb8 $36) 15... Bb4 $1 {there are some concrete lines, but White also risks a lot.} 16. Rxb2 Bxc3+ 17. Kd1 (17. Rd2 $2 Ne4 18. e3 Bxd2+ 19. Ke2 fxe3 20. fxe3 Bb4 $15 {[%csl Ra2] Strong counterplay against a2. The engine thinks that Black is better.}) 17... Bxb2 18. Kc2 Ba3 19. e3 fxe3 20. fxe3 Be6 21. Bd3 g6 22. Rf1 Nd5 $44 {Full or more than full compensation, according to the engine.}) 13. Nxf7 Rg8 14. Ne5 {most logical move, but it leads to equality:} (14. g3 Rb8 15. Rd2 Bb4 $36 {Black has great counterplay.}) 14... Rb8 15. Nxd7 Nxd7 16. g3 (16. Rd2 $6 Ne5 $36 {[%cal Gf8b4,Ge5c4] Nc4 or Bb4 next, could be unpleasant for White.}) 16... Rxb2 17. Bh3 Nf6 18. O-O Bb4 $11 {Equal endgame. In conclusion, we can say that the move 6.Ndb5 does not offer White any real chances to fight for an advantage. The only practical concern is being prepared to play a position without a pawn, but I hope this analysis has given you the confidence to handle this variation. Furthermore, in many cases, Black can even play for more than equality.} *

