{[%evp 0,26,20,-6,16,16,11,22,15,22,6,14,12,-10,0,10,-8,-8,-10,-10,-7,0,40,28,16,34,30,23,29]} 1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e6 6. Bf4 {This is probably White's most interesting sideline.} (6. e3 {harmless.} Bb4 7. Bd2 (7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O d5 9. cxd5 exd5 $36 {Black has a fantastic version of IQP positions.}) (7. Ndb5 a6 8. Nd6+ Ke7 $1 {our king will be in the center, but we will have a huge lead in development:} 9. Nxc8+ Rxc8 10. Bd2 Bxc3 11. Bxc3 Ne4 12. Qc2 (12. Rc1 {Iszak-Bogner, 2014.} Qb6 $1 13. Bxg7 Rhg8 14. Bc3 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Qc5 $36 {[%cal Gc6e5,Ye5c4] Ne5 next.}) 12... Nxc3 13. Qxc3 Qa5 14. Qxa5 Nxa5 15. b3 Rhd8 $36 {Pleasant initiative.}) (7. Qc2 d5 $11 {Just good.}) 7... O-O 8. a3 (8. Bd3 d5 9. cxd5 Nxd4 10. exd4 Nxd5 $11 {very comfortable for Black.}) (8. Be2 d5 9. cxd5 exd5 $36 {also very good version of IQP.}) 8... Be7 (8... Bc5 {is also good.}) 9. Be2 d5 10. cxd5 Nxd4 11. exd4 Nxd5 $11 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gc8d7] Bf6-Bd7 next, no problem.}) (6. Bg5 {I don't understand this move.} h6 7. Bh4 Qb6 8. Bxf6 (8. Nb3 Be7 $36 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d5] 00 and d5 next.}) 8... gxf6 9. Nb3 Qc7 $36 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] b6-Bb7 next and I prefer Black because of the two bishops.}) (6. Nc2 {allows} d5 $1 7. cxd5 (7. e3 Bd6 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O dxc4 10. Bxc4 a6 $17 {It is an unbelievably good version for Black of the QGA structure.}) 7... exd5 8. e3 (8. Bg5 $2 d4 $1 9. Ne4 Bf5 10. Nxf6+ gxf6 11. Bd2 Bc5 $19 {Black's development is so good that the engine already shows -3,00.}) 8... Bd6 {Black gets a fantastic version of IQP:} 9. Be2 (9. Nxd5 $2 O-O 10. Be2 Qa5+ 11. Nc3 Rd8 12. Bd2 Qg5 13. O-O Bc7 $15 {We are too active.}) 9... O-O 10. O-O Be5 $15 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gf8d8,Gd5d4] We can always play d4 or continue more ambitiously with Qe7-Rd8 and maybe then d4.}) (6. Nxc6 dxc6 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {Similar to the 6.e4 line, but now the moves e4-Bc5 have not been included.} 8. Bf4 $1 {[%cal Re6e5] White prevents e5.} (8. Bg5 e5 $15 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gc8e6] Be6-Kc7 next.}) 8... Nd7 $1 $146 {[%cal Gf7f6,Ge6e5] It's very important for us to play e5.} 9. O-O-O f6 $11 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gd8c7] e5-Kc7 next, with an equal endgame.}) 6... d5 7. cxd5 {White's most interesting try.} (7. Ndb5 e5 {trans in 6.Ndb5.}) (7. e3 Bb4 {Black gets an easy game. We can orientate on two games played by GM Erdos.} 8. Nxc6 (8. Be2 dxc4 9. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 10. Rxd1 bxc6 11. Bxc4 Nd5 $11 {No problems for Black as happened in the game Moroni-Erdos, 2023.}) 8... bxc6 9. Qa4 a5 10. Qxc6+ Bd7 11. Qc7 Qxc7 12. Bxc7 Ke7 $1 $44 {[%cal Gh8c8] Rhc8 next and Black had a very good compensation in Gaiewsky-Erdos, 2014.}) (7. a3 $5 {Has been tried by some strong players like Deac, Bachman, and Kuzubov. 7.a3 is mainly an attempt to get a new position.} Be7 8. e3 O-O 9. Be2 (9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 exd5 $132 {[%cal Ge7f6] Bf6 next, and it's comfortable for Black.}) 9... Nxd4 10. Qxd4 (10. exd4 $6 dxc4 11. Bxc4 Bd7 $15 {[%cal Gd7c6] Bc6 next.}) 10... dxc4 11. Qxc4 Bd7 $11 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gd7c6] Rc8-Bc6 next, and it's equal. Very often, our queen will go to a5.}) 7... Nxd5 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bd2 {White hopes to play a long game with a slightly better structure, and this looks like a sensible positional idea.} Bb4 {We immediately want to take everything on c3.} 10. Qa4 $5 {The most critical move, in my opinion.} (10. Nxd5 {This is immediately equal:} Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 cxd5 $11) (10. Rc1 Rb8 $1 {[%csl Gb8] our rook will be useful on the 'b' file.} 11. Qc2 O-O $132 {[%cal Gd8a5] Qa5 next, with a good counterplay.}) (10. Qc2 {White's most common continuation.} Nxc3 11. Bxc3 {standard move, but it's immediately equal after} (11. a3 Nxe2 {trans to 10.a3}) 11... Qa5 12. Bxb4 Qxb4+ 13. Qd2 a5 $11) (10. a3 $5 {tricky concrete move.} Nxc3 (10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 $14 {[%cal Ge2e4] e4 next and it could be slightly better for White.}) 11. Qc2 $1 {White's idea.} Nxe2 $1 {we need to take material.} 12. Bxb4 Nd4 13. Qc3 Qd5 $1 $13 {Interesting position where we can play for three results, for example:} 14. O-O-O (14. Bd3 {also here we have many good moves.} Bb7 15. Rd1 Qe5+ 16. Kf1 O-O-O $13) 14... c5 $1 15. Bc4 {we have many good moves, but the position is complicated.} (15. Bxc5 $6 Nb3+ 16. Kc2 Qxc5 17. Kxb3 Rb8+ 18. Kc2 Qxc3+ 19. Kxc3 Bb7 $36 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Ge8e7,Gh8c8]}) 15... Qg5+ $5 16. Kb1 cxb4 (16... O-O 17. Bxc5 Qxc5 18. Qxd4 Qc7 $11 {safe equality.}) 17. Qxb4 (17. Qxd4 $2 O-O $17) 17... a5 18. Qd6 Qe7 $11) 10... Bxc3 $5 $146 {my recommendation.} (10... Qb6 {Black's most common continuation, but I don't like it.} 11. a3 Bxc3 12. bxc3 $14 {Could easily be slightly better for White.}) (10... Rb8 {also deserves attention, and it has been tried by Grischuk:} 11. e4 Nxc3 12. bxc3 {Artemiev-Grishuk.} Bd6 $1 13. Qxc6+ Ke7 $44) 11. bxc3 (11. Bxc3 {we have now two good ways:} O-O (11... Nxc3 12. Qxc6+ Bd7 13. Qxc3 Rc8 14. Qd2 Qb6 $44 {For sure full compensation because of our active pieces.}) 12. Bd2 Qf6 {the engine thinks that it should end in a draw after} 13. e4 Qxb2 14. Rc1 Qe5 15. Rc5 Qa1+ 16. Rc1 Qe5 $11) 11... Nb6 $1 {[%csl Gc4] our idea is to fight for the c4 square.} (11... O-O $6 12. e4 Nb6 13. Qc2 $14) 12. Qxc6+ {critical.} (12. Qb4 Ba6 $132) (12. Qc2 Nc4 $1 13. Bc1 Ba6 14. e3 Qa5 $36) 12... Bd7 13. Qf3 (13. Qe4 O-O 14. e3 Qc7 $44 {[%cal Gd7c6]}) 13... Nc4 $44 {[%csl Gc4] The position is not concrete, but I am sure that we have full compensation.} *

