1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O d6 $1 {first thing to know is that we start with d6. In this chapter, we'll check 7.d3 and White's 7th moves sidelines to the 7.d4 mainline, which will be covered in Chapter 7.} ({we don't play} 6... O-O {because after} 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 {[%cal Rd7d6] it's more difficult for us to play d6. Of course, 8...d6 and 8..Nxd4 are important lines here, but they are not our recommendation.}) 7. d3 (7. b3 {dubious because it allows} Ne4 $1 8. Bb2 Nxc3 9. Bxc3 (9. dxc3 {[%csl Rb2]} Bf5 $15 {[%csl Rb2] Bb2 is terrible.}) 9... e5 {good solution.} (9... Bxc3 $6 10. dxc3 O-O 11. Ne1 $14 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Ge1c2,Gc2e3] Nc2-Ne3 next, and White can be slightly better.}) 10. d3 O-O 11. Nd2 Be6 12. a3 a5 $11 {[%cal Gd6d5] d5 next, and Black is at least not worse.}) (7. e3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc5d4,Ge3d4] White's idea is d4-cxd4-exd4.} Be6 $5 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ge6c4] we immediately pressure c4.} (7... O-O 8. d4 cxd4 9. exd4 d5 $11 {also fine.}) 8. b3 (8. Qe2 Qc8 9. d4 Bg4 $1 10. Qd2 (10. d5 $2 Ne5 $17 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4]}) 10... h5 11. h4 Nh7 $36 {[%csl Rd4,Gh7]}) (8. d3 {White can play d3, but then he lost the d4 idea:} O-O $11) 8... Ne4 $1 {[%csl Re3,Ge6] same story as 7.b3, but even better version for Black because Be6 is more useful than e3:} 9. Bb2 Nxc3 10. Bxc3 Bxc3 11. dxc3 h6 $15 {[%cal Rf3g5,Gd8d7,Ge6h3,Ge8c8] Qd7-000 next. White doesn't even have the Ne1-Nc3-Ne3 plan.}) (7. a3 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gb2b4] White plans Rb1-b4.} O-O 8. Rb1 d5 $5 {the simplest solution.} 9. cxd5 (9. b3 dxc4 10. bxc4 Ne8 11. Bb2 b6 $132 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gd8d7,Gc6a5] Qd7-Bb7-Na5 next.}) 9... Nxd5 10. Nxd5 (10. Ng5 e6 11. Nge4 b6 12. d3 h6 $15 {Illescas-Anand, 1996.}) 10... Qxd5 11. d3 {Now Black should prepare c4 in a precise way:} (11. b4 $4 {blunder because of} Qa2 {[%csl Rb1]} 12. Qb3 Be6 $1 $19 {[%csl Rb1] White loses material.}) 11... Qa2 $1 {[%csl Rb1][%cal Ga2b1,Gc5c4]} (11... c4 $2 12. Nd2 $16) 12. Bd2 (12. Qc2 $6 {even worse:} Bf5 {[%cal Gc5c4]} 13. Bd2 c4 $1 $15) 12... c4 $1 {Black is fine, for example} 13. Bc3 cxd3 14. Bxg7 (14. Qxd3 Bf5 15. e4 Bxc3 $36) 14... dxe2 15. Qxe2 Kxg7 16. Ng5 $44 {White will have full-compensation if he plays like an engine, but not more for sure.}) 7... O-O 8. a3 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gb2b4] White plans Rb1-b4.} (8. e4 $6 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gf3e1,Ge1c2,Gc2e3] bad version of Botvinnik because Nf3 is misplaced.} a6 $1 $15 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Ga8b8,Gb7b5] Rb8-b5 next, or sometimes even b5 immediately.}) (8. h3 {[%cal Gc8h3] allows} b6 $132 {[%cal Gc8b7] the key point is that after the typical} 9. Ne5 $2 dxe5 10. Bxc6 {[%csl Rh3] now h3 is hanging.} Bxh3 $17) (8. Bf4 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gd1d2,Gf4h6] White's idea is Qd2-Bh6, but I don't think that Bf4 stays well here.} h6 $5 9. Qc1 (9. Qd2 $6 {now we can win the two bishops.} g5 10. Be3 Ng4 $15 {[%csl Re3]}) 9... Kh7 $132 {[%csl Rc1,Rf4] Bf4 and Qc1 look strange.} (9... g5 $6 {doesn't make sense now because White can just play} 10. Bd2 $14)) (8. Bg5 h6 $132 {even better version for us than 8.Bf4.}) (8. Bd2 a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] we play for b5.} (8... h6 {[%csl Gd2,Rf4] now I don't like it, because we play a neutral move, but White's Bd2 could be useful for the a3-b4 plan.} 9. a3 $14 {[%csl Gd2,Rh6][%cal Ga1b1]}) 9. Qc1 {[%cal Gd2h6] White plays for Bh6.} (9. a3 Rb8 10. Rb1 b5 11. cxb5 axb5 12. b4 cxb4 13. axb4 Be6 $132 {[%csl Yd2][%cal Gd8d7] Qd7 next. No problems for Black and it also transposes to Chapter 15.}) 9... Rb8 10. Bh6 b5 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 $132 {Just a position where we cannot be worse.}) 8... Qd7 $5 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] Interesting extra option to have a more complicated game. We prepare b6-Bb7.} (8... a6 {also possible.} 9. Rb1 Rb8 10. b4 cxb4 11. axb4 b5 12. cxb5 axb5 {transposes in Chapter 15.}) (8... b6 $6 {not good immediately because of} 9. Ne5 $1 dxe5 10. Bxc6 $14) 9. Rb1 b6 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gd7c6,Rf3e5] Thanks to Qd7, White doesn't have now Ne5 ideas.} 10. b4 Bb7 {[%cal Gc6d4,Yf6g4,Yg4e5] we can continue with Nd4, or Ng4-Nge5, or just normal moves. It's an equal fighting position.} 11. Bd2 {most common continuation.} (11. b5 $6 Nd4 $1 $36 {good for Black, important to notice that} 12. Nxd4 $2 {would be a positional mistake.} Bxg2 13. Kxg2 cxd4 $17) (11. e3 {[%cal Rc6d4] White stops Nd4.} e6 12. Bd2 {[%cal Gc6e5] we are fine after every move.} Rad8 $5 (12... Ng4 $5) (12... h6 $5 {[%csl Gg7][%cal Gf6h7,Gh7g5,Gf7f5] with Nh7 idea. Sometimes f7-f5 then.})) (11. Qa4 Rfd8 12. Bd2 e6 $132 {[%cal Gc6e7,Yd6d5,Yd7e7] Qe7 or Ne7 next. It's just a game.}) 11... Nd4 {this is not necessary, but it's good.} ({Black can also just continue with} 11... e6 $132) 12. e4 {probably the best.} (12. e3 Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Ng4 $5 $132 {[%cal Gf7f5] f5 next, and it's a balanced position where we can also play for the full point.}) 12... e6 13. Nxd4 {critical continuation.} (13. Ne2 {not critical.} Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3 h5 $132) 13... cxd4 14. Ne2 b5 $1 {strong move.} (14... e5 15. f4 $36 {could be some initiative for White.}) 15. Nxd4 (15. cxb5 Qxb5 {[%csl Rd3] White has problems with d3.} 16. Qb3 Bxe4 $1 {[%csl Re2]} 17. dxe4 Qxe2 $13) 15... bxc4 {[%csl Re4] White has problems with e4.} 16. dxc4 Nxe4 $11 *

