{[%evp 0,30,27,-26,16,16,12,18,10,12,10,6,19,1,-4,18,18,26,26,-4,0,10,10,15,15,2,20,8,20,39,27,17,19]} 1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O {The main issue with castling first is that Black can play d6.} (6. d4 {If White starts with d4 immediately, we don't have time for d7-d6.} cxd4 7. Nxd4 O-O 8. O-O d6 {is anyway a good move here, but it is not the same, because we sacrifice the pawns on c6. This is not our recommendation.} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bxc6 Rb8 {Black needs to study a lot of lines just to make a draw. I think you can achieve if you do a good job, but you are playing for one result: only for a draw.}) 6... d6 {And Black is in time to develop the bishop to d7, to support c6.} 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 {[%csl Gd6,Gd7,Yh8][%cal Gc6d4,Ge8g8,Ga7a6,Gb7b5,Ga8b8,Yh7h5,Yh5h4] We are in time comparing to 6.d4. Black's position is very flexible, because Black didn't castle yet. This means that we can either play the normal plan of 0-0-Nxd4-Bc6 or Rb8-a6-b5, but we have the alternative plan of h5-h4, because the rook is still on h8.} 9. Nc2 {is the main line.} (9. b3 $5 {is an interesting move, White wants to develop the bishop on a good square.} h5 {is my recommendation.} (9... O-O {is possible, but White can also play.} 10. Bb2 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Bc6 12. Qd2 $132 {[%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1] Nothing serious, but playable for White.}) 10. Bb2 {This is a serious variation.} (10. h4 Ng4 {[%csl Rd4] Problems with the knight.} 11. Nxc6 {is not great, because of} (11. e3 {As usual, I don't like.} O-O 12. Bb2 Nxd4 13. exd4 Rb8 $36 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5] Very easy play for Black-}) 11... bxc6 12. Qd3 {White should probably control the g5 square.} (12. Bb2 $2 g5 $1 {Typical idea.} 13. hxg5 h4 $17 {Black is already seriously better.}) 12... O-O $36 {[%cal Gg4e5,Gg7a1] The pieces are very active.}) 10... h4 {White has a choice: Nd5 or Nxc6.} 11. Nxc6 $5 {is more interesting, in my opinion.} (11. Nd5 {is more common, but maybe less strong.} Ne5 {[%cal Gf6d5] The easiest, to prepare Nxd5.} 12. Nxf6+ (12. Nf3 {was played in the game Bok-Adhiban.} Nxd5 13. Nxe5 Nc7 $1 {Very strong move.} 14. Nd3 Bxb2 15. Nxb2 hxg3 16. hxg3 Bc6 $36 {[%cal Gd8d7,Ge8c8] Black is doing great, probably some initiative.}) 12... Bxf6 13. Bxb7 {Yilmaz-Cheparinov, Gibraltar 2020. It's quite risky to take the pawn.} (13. Qd2 $2 {Fernandez-Makarian.} hxg3 14. hxg3 Qc8 $17 {Black is just better.}) 13... Rb8 14. Bd5 {To defend c4.} hxg3 {seems even stronger.} (14... e6 {was played in the game, but maybe it's not so good.} 15. Bg2 Nxc4 16. Bc3 $13 {Still, objectively fine for Black, but some weaknesses in the position exist.}) 15. hxg3 Kf8 $1 $13 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gd8g8,Gg8h7,Gd8c8] 0.00 according to the engine, but looks very dangerous for White.}) 11... Bxc6 {We take with the bishop.} (11... bxc6 12. Ne4 {White has something here.}) 12. Nd5 Kf8 {We don't rush with taking on g3, because we can always take.} 13. Nxf6 {is logical.} (13. e4 {was played in one game, but after} Nd7 14. Bxg7+ Kxg7 {Black just has a very good position.} 15. Qd4+ e5 $11 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gc5e6,Ge6d4]}) 13... Bxf6 14. Bxf6 exf6 {Despite it might seem that the structure is bad for us, the position is absolutely fine.} 15. Bxc6 {Better for White to take on c6.} (15. e4 {In case of e4, we have long term play after} Kg7 16. Qd3 h3 17. Bh1 Qa5 18. Qxd6 Rad8 19. Qf4 Rd3 $17 {This is already serious advantage for Black, because of domination.} 20. Rad1 Rxd1 21. Rxd1 Rd8 22. Qc1 Rxd1+ 23. Qxd1 Qxa2 $19 {The position is already -5.}) 15... bxc6 16. Qd4 Kg7 17. Rad1 {White can take the d6 pawn, but it's okay.} Qa5 18. Qxd6 Qxa2 19. Qxc6 Qxe2 {We make some exchanges.} 20. Rfe1 $1 {[%csl Rg1,Gg7] is the only move to equalize, but Black has some initiative, becuase of the safer king.} Qb2 $11 {But of course, for engine it's equal.}) (9. Nxc6 Bxc6 $5 {That's why this is my recommendation.} (9... bxc6 {Strategically is fine, but in practice it can be a bit annoying after} 10. c5 $5 d5 {Normal continuation.} 11. e4 {White's idea.} dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 O-O $11 {Engine shows +0.15, but it's a 2 results game. Black doesn't really have winning chances and potentially some small problems to solve, so I prefer to avoid it.}) 10. e4 {The most common move.} (10. Bxc6+ $2 {Just a mistake.} bxc6 {[%csl Rg1] White will have long term problems with the king.} 11. c5 {is another story now.} d5 $15 {[%cal Re2e4] No e4 move.}) (10. Nd5 {is a logical move, but Black can just} Nxd5 11. cxd5 Bd7 {And the positions are fine for Black, for example:} 12. Be3 {[%cal Ge3d4] With idea Bd4.} Qa5 $5 {Slightly more precise so that we have no problem with the queen development.} 13. Bd4 Bxd4 14. Qxd4 O-O $11 {White has more space, but we have a good bishop, so there is nothing to be worried about.}) 10... h5 $1 {Now we can go for the h5 plan.} 11. h3 {[%cal Rh5h4,Gg3g4] is a normal way to face h5 ( if h4, g4 is the idea).} (11. Bg5 {seems like it stops h5, but Black can play} Nh7 {[%cal Gh5h4] And h4 next.} 12. Bd2 h4 $132 {Engine shows a good evaluation, even if our pawn is on h4, so this means the position is good for Black.}) 11... Nd7 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5,Ga8c8,Ge8h8] New position, but it seems good for us.} 12. Bd2 a6 13. a4 {To stop b5.} (13. Rc1 b5 $36 {Black is doing very well.}) 13... O-O 14. b3 Rc8 15. Rc1 Nc5 {How can the game continue? I need to invent, because there are no games here.} 16. Qc2 b5 $5 {is maybe already good.} 17. axb5 axb5 18. cxb5 Bxc3 $1 {is a strong intermezzo.} 19. Qxc3 Bxb5 20. Bh6 {is well met with} Ne6 $1 {[%csl Gg7][%cal Gb5f1] And the position simplifies.} 21. Qxc8 Qxc8 22. Rxc8 Rxc8 23. Rc1 Rxc1+ 24. Bxc1 Nd4 $15 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Rd4e2] We won a pawn.}) (9. e3 {I don't like, now we can definitely play} h5 $1 10. h4 {This usually is a great inclusion for Black.} (10. h3 $6 {is not a great idea, because after} Nxd4 11. exd4 Qc8 $1 $40 {[%csl Rc4,Rh3][%cal Rc8c4,Rd7h3] We win a pawn, this is a typical trick.}) 10... O-O 11. b3 a6 {The easiest plan.} 12. Bb2 Rb8 {[%cal Gc6d4,Yb7b5] Our idea is to take on d4 and play b5.} 13. Rc1 (13. Qd2 Nxd4 14. exd4 b5 $36 {Absolutely fine position for Black.}) 13... Qa5 {is another plan.} (13... Nxd4 {is also okay, but the rook is improved in this case.} 14. exd4 b5 $11 {Still position is just equal.}) 14. Qd2 Rfc8 {seems very good for Black.} 15. Rfd1 Nxd4 16. exd4 b5 $36 {Already some small initiative for Black.}) (9. Nb3 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Yc4c5] The knight on b3 is misplaced, the only justification is to play c5.} Qc8 {Black had more than one good move, but this is my suggestion. What is the idea?} 10. Bg5 {A mix of ideas, White keeps c5 for later.} (10. c5 {White achieves their plan.} dxc5 11. Nxc5 Bh3 $36 {[%csl Rc1,Gg7] This is the idea, we exchange the bishop, and we will play a normal position with the g7 bishop against the c1 bishop. Black is at least not worse, and maybe has an initiative.}) 10... h6 11. Bxf6 (11. Bf4 Bh3 $11 {No problem for Black.}) 11... Bxf6 12. c5 $146 {is maybe more interesting.} (12. Qd2 {This was the game Bacrot-Bluvsthein.} Bg7 $5 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7h3] To defend h6, preparing castle and Bh3. Black has a good position.}) 12... dxc5 13. Nxc5 Bh3 14. Nd5 {The critical move.} O-O 15. Nxf6+ exf6 16. Bxh3 Qxh3 17. Qd7 {is probably the best for White.} (17. Nxb7 $6 {If White takes the pawn, we have very strong initiative.} Ne5 {[%cal Ge5g4] Ng4 is a big threat.} 18. f3 Rab8 $36 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gb8b2] The rook on b2 will be very active.}) 17... Qh5 {To maintain the queens, and some professional draw like this:} 18. Qxb7 Qxc5 19. Rac1 Qb4 20. Qxc6 Qxb2 21. Rc2 Qe5 $11 {Just equality.}) (9. e4 {[%csl Rg2] is a possible move, but it closes the bishop on e2, that's why, White usually doesn't want to play it.} Nxd4 (9... h5 $5 {also possible, if you want to be creative.}) 10. Qxd4 O-O 11. Qd3 Ng4 $132 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gg4e5,Ga8c8,Ya7a6,Yb7b5] Looks very fine for Black.}) 9... Qc8 {[%cal Gd7h3,Gh7h5] Maybe we will play it in the future, but not right now.} (9... h5 {I don't like this move here, because after} 10. h4 Ng4 {[%csl Gc2,Rd4] is our usual response, but there we don't get a tempo against the knight.} 11. Nd5 $36 {White has something here.}) 10. b3 $5 {is the most interesting move for White.} (10. Bg5 {Possible move, but Black has no problem after} h6 11. Bf4 Bh3 $132 {Good position.}) (10. Ne3 Bh3 11. Ncd5 Bxg2 {Usually Black takes and goes for something like:} (11... h5 $5 {But I wanted to show you, that sometimes you can even play h5 immediately.} 12. Nc7+ (12. Bxh3 $6 Qxh3 13. Nc7+ $4 {This is just lost.} Kd8 14. Nxa8 Ng4 $19 {Mate in a few moves is coming.}) 12... Qxc7 13. Bxh3 {seems that White won an important bishop, but after} h4 $1 {It is not so easy.} 14. Bg2 e6 $13 {Even this positions are absolutely fine for Black.}) 12. Kxg2 h5 13. h4 Ne5 $15 {And just plays a game with no problems.}) (10. Nd5 Nxd5 {Taking is also fine.} (10... Bh3 $5 {also here this is possible, with similar ideas to 10.Ne3.}) 11. cxd5 Ne5 12. Be3 (12. Ne3 Nc4 $36 {We can exhchange the knights, with a very good position.}) (12. Rb1 Bh3 $36) 12... Nc4 13. Bd4 {Zubarev-Aveskulov, but Black just took the pawn.} Nxb2 14. Qb1 Bxd4 15. Nxd4 Na4 $17 {And later won the game.}) (10. Re1 $6 {was tried in some games, with the idea to avoid the bishop trade.} Bh3 11. Bh1 {But actually after} h5 $1 $17 {Black already has a huge advantage.}) 10... Bh3 11. Bb2 {And now important moment:} O-O {We play castle.} (11... h5 $6 {We don't play with h5, because} 12. f3 {can be tricky.} h4 13. g4 $36 {[%csl Gb2,Gc3] And White's pieces are pretty good already.}) 12. Ne3 {is the most popular move.} (12. Rb1 {was tried in some games, and now I show you a typical plan:} Rd8 13. e4 {When White plays e4, we can} Bxg2 14. Kxg2 e6 $11 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gc8c7,Gd8d7,Ga8d8,Ga8b8,Ga8c8] And then just play a very slow game.}) (12. Rc1 {is similar.} Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Rd8 $11 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gd6d5]}) (12. Nd5 $2 {is a mistake, because in the following line:} Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Nxd5 14. Bxg7 Nf4+ $1 {is a strong intermezzo.} 15. gxf4 Qg4+ $1 16. Kh1 Kxg7 {And White doesn't get what he wants.} 17. Qd2 {Graf-Jason. Black played a normal move, but maybe} e5 $5 {was even stronger.} 18. fxe5 dxe5 $15 {Black is just slightly better here.}) 12... Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Rd8 {We keep more pieces on the board.} (13... Ne4 $6 {Black often tried Ne4, but once you exchange all the pieces after} 14. Rc1 Nxc3 15. Bxc3 Bxc3 16. Rxc3 $14 {The position is pleasant for White.}) 14. Qd2 e6 15. Rab1 a6 $11 {[%cal Gd8d7,Gc8d8,Gc8c7,Ga8e8,Yd6d5,Yb7b5] You have all the time in the world to improve the pieces as you wish, and later on play for either b5 or d5. White's problem is that they have no sensible plan, so you don't need to rush with a pawn break.} *

