{[%evp 0,32,25,-22,21,8,19,19,11,8,8,8,6,13,5,3,30,14,9,25,20,32,32,6,6,25,24,29,22,-5,-15,-90,3,-3,22]} 1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 h5 $5 {This is our recommendation. We follow the last trends of young strong GMs. The biggest expert of this line is GM Sindarov.} 8. h3 {[%cal Rh5h4,Gg3g4] White positionally stops h4 because if 8...h4 now, after 9.g4 White is better.} (8. e3 $6 {is bad because it just allows our idea} h4 $15) (8. Nxc6 $6 dxc6 $1 {we should welcome the endgame.} 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 $36 {[%csl Rc4,Gc6,Rg2,Gh5][%cal Gh5h4,Gg7a1] h5 is very useful move also in the endgame.}) (8. b3 $6 {also allows} h4 9. Nxc6 {Dautov-Maghsodloo} dxc6 $1 {again, we should welcome the endgame:} 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Bb2 Kc7 $36 {[%csl Yh4][%cal Gc8f5,Yh4h3,Yh4g3]}) (8. Nf3 {[%cal Rh5h4] Important move because White stops h4.} d6 9. O-O Be6 $1 $146 {[%csl Rc4] we start an immediate counterplay against c4.} 10. Nd5 (10. b3 $2 {[%cal Gc1b2] doesn't work because of} Ne4 $1 $17) 10... Rc8 11. Bg5 O-O {we are not afraid of Nxf6.} (11... Nh7 {also possible.}) 12. Bxf6 (12. Nxf6+ exf6 $15 {[%csl Rc4] c4 is hanging.}) 12... Bxf6 $1 (12... exf6 $6 13. b3 $14) 13. Nxf6+ exf6 {[%cal Gd6d5] we are ready to play d5, for example:} 14. Qa4 (14. b3 {[%csl Rd6,Rf6]} d5 $11) 14... Qb6 15. b3 d5 $11) (8. O-O {allows} h4 9. c5 {the most critical move in my opinion.} (9. b3 $6 {Black is better in an instructive way:} hxg3 10. hxg3 Ng4 {[%csl Rd4]} 11. e3 Nh2 $3 12. Re1 d5 $3 {[%cal Gc8g4] Bg4 next.} 13. cxd5 Bg4 14. dxc6 $1 {only move.} (14. f3 $4 Nxd4 15. exd4 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Bxd4+ $19) 14... Bxd1 15. cxb7 Bf3 $1 {best move to fight for the advantage, but we can have the equality in many other ways.} 16. Nxf3 Bxc3 17. bxa8=Q Qxa8 18. Nxh2 Qd8 19. Bb2 Bxb2 20. Rab1 Bf6 $15 {[%cal Ge8f8,Gf8g7,Gd8a5] we have very good pieces and only we can play for a win.}) (9. Bg5 {main move.} h3 {my recommendation.} (9... hxg3 10. fxg3 $1 $146 {playable, but could be interesting for White.}) 10. Bh1 O-O $146 {[%csl Gh3] Just a good position for us, for example:} 11. Rc1 (11. c5 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Nh7 13. Qe3 Nxg5 14. Qxg5 e6 $11) 11... Qa5 $5 {instructive plan:} 12. Bf4 Qh5 13. Bf3 Qh8 $132 {[%csl Gh8] Qh8 is very useful.}) 9... hxg3 (9... Rh5 {difficult to say if it's better to start with 9...Rh5 or with 9...hxg3.}) 10. hxg3 (10. fxg3 {[%csl Gc1,Rc5] now it's not dangerous:} Ng4 $1 11. Rf4 {only move.} (11. Nf3 $2 Qa5 $17) 11... d5 $1 12. Nxd5 Bxd4+ 13. Rxd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 e5 15. Qc4 Rxh2 16. Bf3 Rh3 17. Kg2 Rh5 $36 (17... Rh2+ {at minimum, we have a draw.})) 10... Rh5 $1 {[%csl Rc5] important move to target c5.} 11. Nb3 {White defends c5 and now we need to play 2 other precise moves:} (11. Bf3 $5 $146 {interesting novelty.} Rxc5 12. Be3 Rc4 (12... d6 $5 {also possible:} 13. Nxc6 Rxc6 14. Bxc6+ bxc6 15. Kg2 Qa5 $44 {Full compensation.}) 13. Rc1 {Engine-style continuation.} (13. Qd3 $2 Ne5 $17) 13... Qa5 14. Nb3 Qf5 15. Nd2 Rg4 16. Kg2 (16. Bxg4 Nxg4 $44 {[%cal Gg4e3] Full compensation.}) 16... d5 17. Nb3 (17. Rh1 $6 d4 $15) 17... Rc4 18. Rh1 Kf8 $13 {new interesting position.}) 11... d5 $1 12. cxd6 Bh3 $1 (12... exd6 $6 13. Bf4 $14) 13. Bxh3 Rxh3 {We are fine, for example:} 14. dxe7 (14. Nb5 Kf8 $1 {good prophylactic move against Nc7.} 15. dxe7+ Qxe7 16. Qd6 Ne4 17. Qxe7+ Kxe7 $36 {[%csl Ga8,Gc6,Ge4,Gg7,Gh3] all our pieces are very active.}) (14. d7+ $6 Qxd7 15. Qxd7+ Nxd7 16. Kg2 Rh5 $15 {we know that endgames are good for us.}) 14... Qxe7 $44 {[%csl Gh3][%cal Ga8d8] Rd8 next. Good counterplay on the 'h' file.}) (8. h4 {[%csl Rh4,Gh5] h5-h4 inclusion is good for Black because we have the g4 square:} Ng4 $1 {[%csl Gg4]} 9. e3 O-O (9... d5 $5 {also possible.} 10. Nxd5 e6 $11) 10. O-O (10. b3 $2 d5 $1 $17) 10... Rb8 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5] we start to prepare a6-b5.} 11. b3 a6 12. Bb2 Nxd4 13. exd4 d6 $132 {[%cal Gb7b5] b5 next and no problem.}) (8. Bf4 $5 {Interesting idea tried by Grischuk.} h4 9. Rc1 h3 $1 $146 (9... Nh5 10. Be3 Nf6 {Grischuk-Sindarov. The game ended in a draw after 11.Bf4 Nh5 12.Be3, but} 11. h3 $1 {was a strong move.} hxg3 12. fxg3 $14) 10. Bf3 Nh7 {[%csl Rd4,Gg7][%cal Gc6e5] We attack Nd4 and prepare Ne5.} 11. Nb3 (11. Nd5 {engine move.} d6 12. Be3 Bd7 (12... Ne5 13. Nb5 $13) 13. O-O Ne5 14. b3 (14. Bh1 $6 Ng4 $36) 14... Nxf3+ 15. Nxf3 Bc6 $132 {playable for three results.}) (11. Be3 Ne5 $132 {[%csl Ge5,Rf3]}) 11... Nf8 {[%cal Gf8e6] we transfer our knight to e6.} 12. O-O Ne6 13. Be3 d6 $132 {[%cal Gc8d7] Also playable for three results. We can say that 8.Bf4 is not a way to fight for the advantage, but it's a possible option for White to get a playable complicated position.}) 8... Nxd4 $1 ({Don't start with} 8... O-O $6 {because after} 9. Be3 $1 $14 {[%csl Yh3,Rh5][%cal Rf6g4] This is the only case where h5-h3 is convenient for White because we don't have Ng4.}) 9. Qxd4 {Difficult to say if it's better to start with d6 or with 00.} O-O {I prefer to start with 9...00, but it doesn't mean that it's the best.} (9... d6 {allows} 10. b3 {White will not be better, but his position will be slightly more pleasant:} O-O 11. Bb2 a6 12. O-O {I am not sure that we can 100% equalize because White managed to play b3-Bb2. OTB, it's of course very playable also for Black.}) 10. O-O (10. b3 $2 {not possible now because of} Ne4 $1 $19 {[%csl Gg7] and this is the advantage of starting with 9...00.}) (10. c5 $5 {extra line for White compared to the 9...d6 move order.} d6 11. cxd6 Ne8 12. Qf4 Nxd6 {[%csl Gd6] Nd6 is not misplaced, but it's good:} 13. O-O Be6 14. Rd1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gc3d5] Rd1-Nd5 is the most logical continuation, in my opinion.} Qb6 (14... Rc8 {also fine.}) 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. Bxd5 Nf5 $132 {[%cal Ge7e6,Ga8d8] White has 2 bishops, but our pieces are very active. It's equal, but the engine slightly prefers Black.}) 10... d6 {[%csl Gh2,Gh7] Doesn't matter if we start with 9...d6 or 9...00, White can always get this position if he wants. Compared to the big main line, the inclusion of h5-h3 favors Black, in my opinion.} 11. Qd3 {White's most common and natural move.} (11. Qh4 {Engine shows this as possible, but it looks a bit strange:} Bd7 (11... Be6 $5) 12. Rd1 (12. Bxb7 Rb8 13. Bg2 Qa5 $36 {[%cal Gf8c8] Rfc8 next, and it's not only compensation, but also initiative.}) 12... Bc6 (12... Rb8 $6 13. c5 $14) 13. c5 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 d5 $13 {Unclear, for example:} 15. e4 {most concrete move} Qc7 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Rxd5 e6 18. Rd1 Qxc5 $11 {no problem.}) (11. Rd1 $5 $146 Be6 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Ye6d5,Gf6d5] we prepare Nd5.} 12. Qh4 Qc8 13. b3 Nh7 14. Bb2 Re8 $5 {might be simpler.} (14... Bf6 {Good to concretely equalize:} 15. Qf4 Bxh3 16. Nd5 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Re8 18. Nxf6+ Nxf6 19. Bxf6 exf6 20. Rxd6 Rxe2 21. Qxf6 Qg4 $11) 15. Na4 Bxb2 16. Nxb2 Bd7 $132 {[%cal Gd7c6] Bc6 next.}) (11. b3 {allows} d5 $5 (11... Be6 {[%cal Gd8d7] Qd7 next is also possible.}) 12. Rd1 Be6 13. Qh4 Qa5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. cxd5 Bxa1 16. dxe6 Bf6 $13 {White has compensation but no more.}) (11. Qd2 Be6 12. Bxb7 Rb8 13. Bg2 Bxc4 14. b3 {Moroni-Lumachi 2024. Black played 14...Nd5 which was good enough to equalize, but} Be6 $1 15. Bb2 Qa5 $36 {was stronger. Rfc8 next, and Black has the initiative.}) 11... Be6 {[%csl Rh3,Gh5][%cal Gd8c8] Compared to the big mainline where the pawns are on h2 and h7, here we have the Qc8 strong resource, and h3 is often hanging.} 12. Bg5 $146 {White's best move, according to the engine.} (12. Bd2 $2 {Would be a mistake now because of} Qc8 $17 {[%csl Rc4,Rh3][%cal Ge6h3,Ge6c4]}) (12. Kh2 {White defends h3, but spends an important tempo:} Rc8 13. b3 (13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. cxd5 Bf5 15. e4 Bd7 $36 {[%csl Gg7][%cal Gd8b6] Qb6 next.}) 13... d5 $1 $17) (12. Bxb7 $6 Bf5 {slightly stronger than the immediate 12...Bh3 because it forces White's queen to go in a worse square.} 13. Qe3 Bxh3 14. Bxa8 (14. Bg2 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Rc8 {[%csl Rc4,Re3]} 16. b3 d5 $1 $17) 14... Qxa8 15. Qf3 Qxf3 16. exf3 Bxf1 17. Kxf1 Nd7 $36 {easy-to-play initiative.}) (12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. cxd5 Bd7 $132 {typical good structure.}) (12. b3 {allows} d5 $1 {which is not necessary, but it immediately equalizes:} 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Bxd5 15. Nxd5 Bxa1 16. Ba3 Bf6 17. Nxf6+ exf6 18. Bxf8 Qxd3 19. exd3 Kxf8 $11 {Iturrizaga-Sindarov, 2024.}) 12... Qc8 {[%csl Rc4,Rh3]} 13. Nd5 {[%csl Rf6,Gg5] 12.Bg5 creates some tactical ideas for White.} Re8 $1 {[%csl Ye7][%cal Gf6d5,Ye8e7] we protect e7 and are ready for Nxd5.} (13... Nxd5 $2 14. cxd5 $16 {[%csl Re7] e7 is hanging.}) 14. Bxf6 {White's most critical try.} (14. Kh2 {allows:} Nxd5 15. cxd5 Bd7 16. Rac1 Qd8 $11 {[%cal Gg7b2,Gd8a5,Gg7f6,Gg5f6,Ge7f6] typical good structure for Black.}) 14... Bxf6 15. h4 {The engine thinks that White is fine also without the pair of bishops because Nd5 is strong, so I recommend to capture it immediately:} (15. Nxf6+ exf6 $15 {[%csl Rc4,Rh3] c4 and h3 are hanging.}) 15... Bxd5 16. Bxd5 Kg7 $11 {This position cannot be worse for us.} *

