{[%evp 0,26,12,-15,19,18,27,18,19,5,23,31,43,37,31,23,25,31,14,14,55,54,53,68,43,71,73,74,76]} 1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e4 {This move looks very strange to me, and it's not often played by strong players.} d6 $5 {This is my recommendation. Our idea is to make the game more interesting.} (4... e5 {is a very solid continuation. We build a symmetrical structure, and it will be difficult for White to demonstrate something. For example:} 5. d3 d6 6. Be2 Be7 7. O-O O-O {Equal position, where I don't see a clear plan for White. In practice, Black has scored better, which means two things: - the 4.e4 line is often chosen by not-so-strong players; - If White starts a concrete plan, this may easily backfire. Why 4...e5 is not my main recommendation then? Because although we are absolutely fine, the position is quite boring, and I prefer to have another option.}) 5. d4 {This is, of course, White's best move.} (5. d3 {if White doesn't go for d2-d4, then after} g6 $15 {[%csl Yd4,Re4][%cal Gf8g7,Yc8g4,Yg4f3,Yc6d4] Our position is already strategically better because White's pawn on e4 is misplaced, and our bishop on g7 will be very strong. In the future, we can continue with Bg4-Bxf3, with the idea to fight for the d4 square.}) 5... Bg4 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Yg4f3] We fight for the d4 square.} (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 $14 {This is playable for Black, but objectively, White is slightly better.}) 6. d5 (6. dxc5 {is not a good idea, because after} dxc5 $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6d4] Only Black can be better thanks to White's weak d4 square.}) 6... Nd4 7. Be2 (7. Be3 Bxf3 $1 8. gxf3 g6 $1 {We are ready to sacrifice a pawn for the dark squares.} 9. Nb5 {It's better for White not to give up his dark squares bishop.} (9. Bxd4 $6 cxd4 10. Qxd4 Bh6 $1 $36 {[%csl Yf4][%cal Ge8g8,Gf6h5,Rf3f4,Yh6f4] We don't allow f3-f4, and we are ready to continue with 00-Nh5. Black has a very strong initiative.}) 9... Nxb5 10. cxb5 Bg7 $132 {It's a fighting position, objectively equal.}) 7... Bxf3 8. Bxf3 g6 {[%csl Gd4] White has two bishops, but we have a strong knight on d4 and a strong bishop on g7 in the near future.} 9. Be3 Bg7 $1 $146 {Once again, we are ready to sacrifice a pawn to have a strong grip on the dark squares as compensation.} (9... Nxf3+ $6 {would be a positional inaccuracy because after} 10. Qxf3 Bg7 11. O-O O-O 12. Qe2 $14 {White is typically better, thanks to the extra space.}) 10. Bxd4 (10. O-O {It's not easy to find a plan for White if he doesn't want to take on d4.} O-O $132 {[%cal Gf6d7,Ga7a6,Gb7b5] Nd7 next. Sometimes we can consider a6-b5 ideas.}) 10... cxd4 11. Qxd4 O-O 12. O-O Nd7 13. Qd2 Qa5 $44 {[%csl Rc4,Rf3][%cal Gf8c8,Gd7e5,Yg7a1] Engine assesses 0.00, but also, from a human point of view, it's absolutely clear that Black has a strong compensation. I don't want to say that we are better, but from a practical point of view, it's easier to play for Black, in my opinion.} *

