{[%evp 0,32,18,-12,19,18,19,19,13,14,11,26,25,2,2,6,11,3,6,11,44,44,39,39,47,43,43,10,11,10,14,-7,6,2,6]} 1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {White prepares d2-d4.} e5 {This is my recommendation.} ({You can also play} 4... e6 5. d4 d5 {but, then, you need to study this very big theoretical position. Black is fine, but a lot of work is required.}) 5. d4 {White's most common continuation, but also 5.Be2 deserves serious attention.} (5. a3 {White plays a useful waiting move, but we can push} d5 $1 {that's why 5.a3 is not very popular among strong players.} 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. Bb5 (7. Qc2 Be7 8. Bb5 O-O 9. O-O (9. Bxc6 $6 bxc6 10. Nxe5 $2 {Would be a huge mistake because of} Bf6 11. Nxc6 Qd7 12. Na5 Nf4 $3 13. exf4 Ba6 $19 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gf8e8,Ga6f1] White is busted.}) 9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 Qd6 $132 {[%cal Gc8g4] Bg4 next, and Black is at least fine.}) 7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 Bd6 $132 {[%cal Ge8g8] 00 next, and Black is at least fine.}) (5. Be2 $5 {This is a serious move against which it's not so obvious how to equalize with Black.} d5 6. d4 (6. cxd5 {This is not interesting for White.} Nxd5 7. O-O Nxc3 8. dxc3 (8. bxc3 $6 e4 $15) 8... Qxd1 9. Rxd1 f6 $11 {[%cal Gc8e6,Gf8e7,Ge8f7] I don't see many problems in this endgame. We can continue with Ba6-Be7-Kf7, and the position is equal.}) 6... exd4 (6... e4 {is also possible, but after} 7. Ne5 dxc4 {White can play many moves, and I don't think that it's that easy for Black to equalize.}) 7. exd4 {This is a very important moment. How to continue?} Be7 {This is my recommendation. The idea is to avoid holdable but unpleasant endgames.} (7... cxd4 {was my first idea, but after} 8. Nxd4 dxc4 9. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 10. Nxd1 bxc6 11. Bxc4 $14 {Objectively, Black is fine, but White has a risk-free endgame, and in practice, he can win one game out of three.}) (7... Be6 {is Black's most common continuation, but after} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. O-O Be7 10. dxc5 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Bxc5 {[%cal Gh7h6]} 13. Ng5 $14 {We have an endgame that objectively it's holdable, but White can play a long game with the pair of bishops, and if you play against a strong endgame player, you may feel a lot of pressure and the situation could become unpleasant.}) 8. Be3 (8. O-O O-O 9. cxd5 {Is not dangerous anymore:} Nxd5 10. Nxd5 (10. dxc5 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxc5 $15 {[%csl Rc3] In this version, only Black can be better because of White's weak queenside structure.}) 10... Qxd5 11. Be3 (11. dxc5 Qxc5 $11 {Absolutely fine for Black.}) 11... cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Qxd4 14. Bxd4 Rd8 15. Rfd1 Bf5 $11 {Just equal.}) 8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 (9... O-O 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. O-O $14 {[%csl Ga2,Gb2] Almost nothing for White, but he has a small pressure that makes his position risk-free, and he may win one game out of 4/5. In practice, White scored 60%.}) 10. Bxd4 (10. Qxd4 dxc4 11. Qxd8+ Bxd8 12. Bxc4 O-O 13. O-O {This is equal in many ways:} a6 $11 (13... Be6 $5 {even this move leads to full equality:} 14. Bxe6 fxe6 $11 {[%csl Ye6][%cal Gg8f7,Gd8e7] The e6 pawn is not a real weakness.})) 10... dxc4 11. Bxc4 O-O 12. O-O a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] our idea is b5-Bb7.} (12... Bg4 $5 {Also deserves attention.}) 13. Bb3 {White plays a prophylactic move, but we can immediately equalize:} (13. Be2 Be6 14. Bf3 Qa5 $11 {[%csl Yb2][%cal Rf3b7,Ga8b8,Gb8b2]}) (13. a4 {[%csl Rb4] We will have the b4 square.} Bg4 14. f3 Bf5 $132) 13... Bg4 14. f3 (14. Qd2 Bc5 $11) 14... Bd7 $11 {[%cal Gd7c6] Bc6 next, with full equality.}) 5... e4 {[%csl Rc1] I recommend playing e4 now, without exchanging on d4, so that White's bishop on c1 cannot be developed for the moment.} (5... cxd4 {I don't want to exchange on d4, because after} 6. exd4 e4 7. Ne5 $14 {[%csl Yc1][%cal Yc1g5] White's bishop on c1 will be able to join the game.}) 6. d5 {White wants to enter in an endgame:} (6. Ng5 {If White moves his knight not on e5, then we can exchange on d4:} cxd4 7. exd4 Bb4 8. d5 $1 {Only move, otherwise Black will be better.} (8. Be2 $6 d5 $15) 8... Bxc3+ $5 9. bxc3 Na5 {This is a very interesting position, but White runs a higher risk:} 10. f3 $1 {This is White's best continuation. Why? Because he needs to solve his knight's g5 problem.} (10. Qd4 $6 O-O 11. Be2 Re8 $15 {[%csl Rg5] White has problems with the knight on g5.}) (10. Ba3 $6 {Normal move, but a serious mistake.} d6 11. c5 O-O $1 12. cxd6 Re8 $17 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gb7b6,Ga5b7,Yh7h6] b6-Nb7 next, and Black has a big positional advantage because our knights have a lot of great squares, while the knight on g5 is very misplaced. For example, White needs to think about h7-h6.}) 10... O-O 11. Be2 d6 12. O-O (12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. fxe4 Qh4+ 14. g3 Qxe4 15. O-O Bh3 $132) 12... Bf5 13. fxe4 Bg6 $1 $132 {[%csl Rc4,Re4][%cal Ga8c8,Gf8e8] Re8-Rc8 next, and we can play against White's weak e4 and c4 pawns. Still, White is a pawn-up right now, and the position is objectively equal.}) (6. Nd2 {Now that White moved his knight on d2, we can exchange on d4.} cxd4 7. exd4 Bb4 $132 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d5] 00-d5 next, and Black is doing great.}) (6. Ne5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Rc5d4] If White wants to move his knight, then this is the best square for it. Remember: unlike in the previous two examples, if White plays Ne5, we do not exchange on d4.} g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8] We want to play Bg7-00. We will analyze this position separately in the next Chapter 11.}) 6... exf3 7. dxc6 dxc6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. gxf3 {In practice, White scored 53%, but this happened mostly because Black players did not fully understand how to play. In my opinion, if we know the key ideas, the endgame is just equal.} g6 {[%cal Gf8g7] First step: we develop our bishop on the strong h8-a1 diagonal.} 10. b3 {This is White's logical continuation because he wants to contest our bishop.} Bg7 11. Bb2 {Now we have a choice that occurs also in the Berlin endgame: where to place our king? e7 or c7? In my opinion, both ideas are fine, but I will suggest playing with the king on c7.} b6 (11... Ke7 {is another very sound approach.}) 12. O-O-O+ Kc7 {This is my recommendation.} 13. h4 $5 {This is White's most tricky continuation. Now, you need to remember that we play waiting moves, and whenever White moves his knight, we will play Nh5.} (13. Ne4 {After this, Black is perfectly fine:} Nh5 $11 {We exchange the bishops and no problems.}) 13... Re8 $1 $146 {I don't want to say that exactly Re8 deserves an exclamation mark, but the correct idea for Black is to play useful waiting moves and be ready for Nh5 once White moves his knight from c3.} (13... Nh5 $6 {Immediately it is not so good because White can play} 14. Be2 $14 {[%cal Gf3f4] With f4 idea. Remember: We play Nh5 only once White has moved his knight from c3.}) (13... Bf5 $6 {This was tried in two games, but I don't like it because of:} 14. Ne2 $1 Nh5 {This would be the logical continuation, but after} (14... h5 $6 {Very serious mistake; now White is better.} 15. Ng3 Be6 16. Be5+ Kb7 17. f4 $16 {Sargissian-Djukic, 2023.}) 15. Bxg7 Nxg7 16. Ng3 $36 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gg3f5] White will for sure manage to play h5 or to take our bishop on f5. The position is still objectively fine, but White has achieved something.}) 14. Bd3 (14. Ne2 Nh5 $1 $11) 14... a5 {another waiting move.} 15. a4 Bd7 {another waiting move. We have plenty of them; next we can play Re8-Rae8.} 16. Ne2 Nh5 $1 $11 {In conclusion, the endgame in the 7.d5 line is equal, but you need to know the best strategy if you play Black, and I am sure that now you will be ready to face it!} *

