{[%evp 0,42,25,-25,17,21,17,16,16,14,8,32,14,6,13,-3,10,21,40,20,28,37,14,22,55,45,40,63,63,40,69,13,0,-13,-9,0,45,44,49,43,32,46,61,61,52]} 1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e5 5. d4 e4 {[%csl Rc1]} 6. Ne5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Rc5d4] If White wants to move his knight, then this is the best square for it. Remember: unlike in the previous two examples, if White plays Ne5, we do not exchange on d4.} g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8] We want to play Bg7-00.} (6... cxd4 $2 {Don't take on d4, because after} 7. exd4 {[%csl Gc1]} g6 8. Bg5 $1 $16 {[%csl Gg5] White is better.}) (6... h5 $5 {also deserves attention.}) 7. g4 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf1g2,Gg4g5] This is the most critical move, in my opinion. White's ideas are g5 or Bg2, playing against our e4 pawn.} (7. Nxc6 {is harmless because after} dxc6 8. dxc5 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Bxc5 $132 {We are at least not worse.}) (7. Rb1 $5 {[%csl Gb1][%cal Yb2b4] Useful waiting move. White's idea is to wait Bg7 and then Nxc6-dxc6-dxc5. Rb1 is useful because White will be able to play b2-b4 later.} h5 $5 {I like this useful-waiting move.} (7... Bg7 {also fine.} 8. Nxc6 dxc6 9. dxc5 {[%csl Rb1][%cal Gb2b4,Rg7a1]} Qe7 $146 {probably the best.} (9... Qa5 {not good because of} 10. b4 $16 {[%csl Gb1] And this was the idea behind 7.Rb1!?}) (9... Bf5 10. Qxd8+ Rxd8 11. Ne2 $5 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc1b2,Ge2d4] b4-Bb2-Nd4 next. It's still equal, but it could potentially become better for White.}) 10. Qd6 {critical.} (10. b4 Ng4 11. Bb2 O-O 12. Be2 Rd8 13. Qc2 a5 $44 {Full compensation for sure.}) 10... Ng4 11. Qxe7+ (11. h3 $6 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Ne5 $15) 11... Kxe7 12. Nxe4 Bf5 13. Bd3 Rad8 14. Bc2 Nf6 15. f3 Nxe4 16. fxe4 Be6 17. b3 Bc3+ 18. Kf2 Rd7 $44 {Despite the two extra pawns, White is not better and we have full compensation.}) 8. Be2 {most logical move, and only now we play} (8. Nxc6 $6 dxc6 {[%csl Gf8] is nothing because our bishop is still on f8, which means that we will be able to play Bxc5 in case of dxc5.} 9. dxc5 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 Bxc5 $15) 8... Bg7 9. Nxc6 dxc6 10. dxc5 Bf5 {[%csl Re2,Gh5][%cal Gf6d7,Rc3e2] Compared to 7...Bg7, thanks to the inclusion of Be2+h5, White doesn't have the Ne2 idea.} 11. Qxd8+ Rxd8 {[%cal Rc3e2]} 12. b4 Nd7 13. Bb2 {We have full compensation after many moves:} a5 14. a3 Ne5 $44) (7. Be2 {most logical move, but not dangerous for us:} Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Rb1 {White's best, according to the engine.} (9. Nxc6 {With the rook on a1 this plan doesn't make sense:} dxc6 10. dxc5 {[%csl Ra1]} Qa5 $15 {[%csl Ra1][%cal Rb2b4] White doesn't have b2-b4 idea.}) (9. h3 $6 {This is a good model game that I want to include in the Chapter:} Re8 (9... h5 $5) 10. Nxc6 dxc6 11. dxc5 Nd7 12. Qc2 Nxc5 13. b4 Nd3 14. Rb1 Qh4 15. Bd2 Bxh3 16. gxh3 Qxh3 $19 {[%cal Ge8e5,Ge5g5] Kjaransson-Nanjo, 2024.}) (9. b3 $6 {most common move, but after} Ne7 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gh7h5,Gd7d6] White has problems with Ne5.} 10. Bb2 (10. Ng4 Ne8 $5 (10... Nxg4 11. Bxg4 f5 12. Be2 Nc6 $15) 11. f3 d5 $15) 10... d6 11. Ng4 Ne8 12. h3 h5 13. Nh2 cxd4 14. exd4 d5 $15 {[%cal Ge8d6,Gf7f5]}) 9... Qe7 10. b3 $1 (10. Nxc6 dxc6 11. dxc5 Qxc5 $15 {Positionally better for Black.}) 10... Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxe5 12. Bb2 Qe7 13. Nb5 Ne8 $132 {White has full compensation for the pawn, but no more.}) 7... h6 $1 {[%cal Rg4g5] We have to stop g5.} 8. Bg2 Bg7 9. h3 {[%csl Yg4] White's best. h3 is a useful move to defend g4.} (9. Nxe4 {is not winning a pawn:} Nxe4 10. Bxe4 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Bxe5 $132 {[%csl Rg4] between equal and slightly better for Black. Now, the g4 pawn is a weakness.}) (9. Nxc6 $2 {also doesn't win a pawn:} dxc6 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 cxd4 $17) (9. h4 {[%cal Gg4g5] White's idea is g5.} d5 $1 10. cxd5 $1 $146 {only good move for White.} (10. g5 $6 hxg5 11. hxg5 Rxh1+ 12. Bxh1 {Li-Borovikov, 2017.} Nh7 $1 $146 {[%csl Rg5,Gh7] typical idea.} 13. cxd5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Bxe5 15. Nxe4 Nxg5 $15) 10... Nxd5 11. Nxe4 (11. Bxe4 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nxc3 13. Qxd8+ Kxd8 14. bxc3 Bxe5 $36 {White needs to be precise in order to equalize.}) 11... cxd4 12. exd4 O-O $44 {For sure, we have full compensation and probably some initiative.}) 9... Qe7 {My recommendation.} (9... O-O {I am not sure about it because of} 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bxe5 13. Bd5 $5 (13. Bxg6 $6 d5 $1 $36 {Sebenik-Babula, 2023.}) 13... d6 14. Qc2 Kh7 15. Bd2 $36 {[%cal Ge1c1] 000 next. For now it's still equal, but in the future it could become better for White.}) 10. b3 $1 {critical and it was played in the game Mamedyarov-MVL, 2018.} (10. Nxc6 $6 dxc6 11. O-O $4 {Sharma-Gabrialian, 2018.} g5 $3 $19 {[%cal Gh6h5] h5 next and Black is winning.} (11... h5 12. g5 $1 $15)) 10... O-O $5 $146 {my recommendation.} (10... Nxe5 $2 {it's a bad idea to accept the pawn:} 11. dxe5 Qxe5 12. Bb2 $16 {White has a lot of ideas on the a1-h8 diagonal and against our e4 pawn.}) (10... cxd4 {I don't like it.} 11. exd4 Nxe5 $2 (11... d5 {[%csl Gc1] was the best, but White has many ideas here because the bishop on c1 is very flexible.}) 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Bb2 d5 14. Qe2 $1 Qe7 15. cxd5 $16 {Mamedyarov-MVL, 2018.}) 11. O-O (11. Bb2 {not so precise:} cxd4 12. exd4 d6 13. Nxc6 bxc6 {[%cal Gd6d5] we are ready to play d5.} 14. d5 (14. O-O $2 d5 $17) 14... Bb7 $36) (11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Ba3 d6 $132) 11... d6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Bb2 (13. dxc5 $6 dxc5 14. Ba3 {[%csl Rg4] We have great counterplay against g4:} h5 $1 15. g5 Nh7 16. Nxe4 Rd8 $36 {[%csl Ra1,Rg5,Rh3][%cal Gg7a1,Gc8h3,Yh7g5]}) 13... h5 14. g5 Nh7 15. Nxe4 $1 {only move.} (15. h4 $2 Bf5 $17 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gf7f6] f6 next and big advantage for Black.}) 15... Bxh3 (15... Nxg5 {also possible:} 16. Nxg5 Qxg5 17. f4 Qe7 $13 {Complicated fighting position.}) 16. Nf6+ $1 (16. Bxh3 $6 Qxe4 $15) 16... Bxf6 17. gxf6 Qd7 (17... Qe6 $5 18. d5 Qf5 $13) 18. dxc5 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Ng5 20. Rh1 Qf5 21. cxd6 Rfe8 $13 {[%cal Ge8e4,Ge4g4] Re4 next and it's a very complicated position. Although it's evaluated by the engine with the classical "0.00", OTB, all the three results are possible.} *

