{[%evp 0,26,27,-26,10,10,12,10,6,6,6,3,9,3,5,13,6,3,3,3,9,9,-10,-10,53,-2,-9,-11,-21]} 1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. a3 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gb2b4] This move has been played in more than 5.000 games, and it was GM Dvirnyy's recommendation. White's idea is to organize a quick queenside counterplay by playing Rb1-b4.} Nf6 {This is my recommendation. For the moment, we want to complete our development.} 6. Rb1 (6. b4 $6 cxb4 7. axb4 Nxb4 $15 {White doesn't have enough compensation for the pawn.}) 6... O-O {We still ignore b2-b4.} 7. d3 {This is less common than 7.b4, but it's White's best move order. Now, we don't have a useful move that would eventually allow us to transpose into the 7.b4 variation.} (7. b4 {Now, Black is fine in more than one way, but I like the following one:} cxb4 8. axb4 a5 $5 {White needs to make an important decision on the queenside.} 9. bxa5 $1 (9. b5 $6 {This move may look logical, but it's a mistake:} Nb4 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gd7d5] Our knight on b4 supports d7-d5.} 10. Ba3 d5 $1 11. Bxb4 (11. cxd5 Nbxd5 $17 {Just better for Black.}) 11... axb4 12. Rxb4 (12. Nxd5 $4 {Losing move!} Bf5 $1 $146 13. d3 (13. Rxb4 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Ra1 $19) 13... Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Bc3+ 15. Kf1 Ra2 $17 {[%csl Gb4] Our b4 pawn is still alive, and White's position is objectively lost.}) 12... dxc4 $1 $146 13. Rxc4 (13. Nf3 Nd5 $17) 13... Be6 {We miss a pawn, but we have a big lead in development. White's best strategy is to sacrifice the b5 pawn to finish the development.} 14. Ra4 {only move.} Qd7 15. Nf3 Nd5 16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. O-O Qxb5 18. Rxa8 Rxa8 $15 {[%csl Gb7] Equal material, but we have a very pleasant b7 passed pawn.}) 9... Rxa5 10. d3 {White delays Nf3 with the idea of not allowing d7-d5, but...} (10. Nf3 $6 {allows} d5 $1 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 $15 {[%csl Yb7] Equal material, but we have the b7 pawn, which gives us nice hopes for the future.}) 10... d5 $1 {We can play it anyway!} 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Rxd5 13. Bxd5 Qxd5 $44 {Pawn down, but we have a very nice compensation. For example:} 14. Nf3 Bc3+ 15. Bd2 Bxd2+ 16. Qxd2 Nd4 $15) (7. Nf3 $6 {just bad because it allows} d5 $15) 7... a6 8. b4 (8. Nf3 d5 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Bd2 {Black is fine after many moves, for example:} Nxc3 11. Bxc3 Bg4 $11) 8... cxb4 9. axb4 b5 10. cxb5 (10. Nf3 d6 11. O-O {White tries to play without cxb5, but after} bxc4 12. dxc4 Bf5 $132 {[%cal Ga8c8] Rc8 next, and Black is at least not worse.}) (10. Nxb5 $5 {was tried, but it doesn't lead to anything special:} axb5 (10... Rb8 $5 {deserves attention.}) 11. cxb5 Ra2 $1 $146 12. Qb3 $1 (12. bxc6 $6 dxc6 13. Nf3 (13. Bxc6 $2 Nd5 $19 {Winning position for Black.}) 13... Ne4 $1 14. dxe4 Qxd1+ 15. Kxd1 Rd8+ $17 {[%cal Gg7c3]}) 12... Nxb4 13. Qxb4 Qc7 $1 {[%cal Gg7c3] We may have Bc3 ideas.} 14. Bd2 Qc2 15. Rc1 Qb2 16. Nf3 Qxb4 17. Bxb4 Nd5 18. Bd2 Rb2 $11 {[%cal Gb2b5] Rxb5 next, and it's a draw.}) 10... axb5 11. Nf3 (11. Nxb5 Rb8 $11 {[%cal Gb8b4] Rxb4 next.}) 11... d6 {[%csl Ga8][%cal Ga8a1,Gd8b8,Yf8c8] My idea is to use this more order to play without Rb8. Ideally, I would like to keep my rook on a8 and play with Qb8-Rc8.} (11... Rb8 {it's a standard move} 12. O-O d6 {would lead to a big theoretical position.}) 12. O-O Be6 $5 $146 {[%cal Gd8b8,Gf8c8] It's a new position, equal according to the engine.} 13. Bd2 (13. Ng5 Bd7 14. Nxb5 Rb8 $11 {Rxb4 next.}) (13. Nxb5 Ba2 14. Rb2 Nd5 $13 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gg7b2] Complicated position, but very likely it will simplify in a draw once White plays some accurate moves and we will take on b4.}) 13... Qb8 $5 $132 {[%cal Gf8c8] Rc8 next, and no problems for Black.} *

