{[%evp 0,28,34,-9,19,18,12,5,5,6,4,4,20,20,21,21,21,23,10,10,18,8,-3,-4,-4,0,0,-19,0,0,31]} 1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. e3 {e3-Nge2 is known as "Fischer set-up". White's idea is to play d4, but Black will also be in time to play d5, after which a lot of exchanges are usually following. That's why this line is considered very drawish.} e6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d5] We copy White's development, and this is considered the most reliable set-up for Black.} 6. Nge2 Nge7 7. O-O (7. d4 {Shouldn't have an independent value:} cxd4 8. exd4 (8. Nxd4 O-O {Difficult to imagine for White a better move than 00, which would transpose in the mainline.} 9. h4 {was tried by Iturrizaga, but it's not clear if it's a good move for White.} d5 10. cxd5 exd5 $132 {[%csl Rh4] Very likely White will need to castle, and I don't think that h4 move was a very useful move for him.}) 8... d5 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 exd5 {Also here, it's difficult to imagine White playing without 00. After 11.00 - 00, we transpose in the mainline.}) 7... O-O 8. d4 {This is White's standard continuation, and the idea of the "Fischer set-up".} (8. Nf4 $6 {[%cal Rd7d5,Rd2d4] White prevents d5, but also d2-d4 will not be possible.} Rb8 $15 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5] We can play for a6-b5. Both sides cannot play their desired central move (d4 for White; d5 for Black), but White's knight on f4 looks misplaced.}) (8. a3 {White plays a waiting move, but after} d5 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. d4 $132 {[%csl Ra3] It's like we are playing White, because I don't think the a2-a3 move was so useful.} cxd4 $5 12. Nxd4 h5 $5 $132) (8. b3 {Is tried from time to time, but mostly in blitz games, when White doesn't want to play d2-d4 which would allow massive exchanges.} d5 9. Ba3 {This is the only interesting continuation for White.} (9. cxd5 exd5 10. d4 Bg4 $15 {[%csl Rb3] The move b2-b3 can easily backfire.}) (9. Bb2 $2 d4 10. Na4 b6 {[%csl Ra4] White's knight on a4 is very misplaced} 11. exd4 cxd4 12. d3 Rb8 $17 {[%csl Ra4]}) 9... Qa5 $5 {More practical than d4.} (9... d4 {is fine, but the position gets very complicated after} 10. Na4 d3 11. Nf4 b6 12. Bb2 e5 $1 13. Nd5 $132 {New position, where it's very difficult to say which side risks more. According to the engine, it's 0.00.}) 10. Qc1 Rd8 $132 {Black has no problems.}) 8... cxd4 {White can now choose if to recapture with the pawn or with the knight.} 9. Nxd4 (9. exd4 d5 10. cxd5 (10. c5 $2 {is a huge mistake:} Nf5 {[%csl Rd4]} 11. Be3 b6 $1 $17 {Black has a very big advantage.}) 10... Nxd5 11. Nxd5 {By far, White's most common continuation.} (11. Qb3 $6 {White doesn't want to capture on d5, but this can backfire:} Nxc3 12. bxc3 {[%csl Rb3] and now we will use White's misplaced queen} Na5 $1 $15 {[%csl Yc4][%cal Gc8d7,Ga8c8] Bd7-Rc8 next, and Black is already preferable.}) ({White can try to keep it slightly more complicated with} 11. h4 {but I have the feeling that after} Qb6 $11 {Massive exchanges are unavoidable anyway.}) (11. Re1 {Same story as 11.h4, after} Qb6 $11 {Maybe Re1 is more useful than h4, but anyway massive exchanges will follow.}) 11... exd5 12. Be3 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Ye3d4,Ge2f4] White protects the d4 pawn, and he hopes to play with Nf4, and that his extra tempo can give him a small advantage.} (12. Qb3 $6 {[%csl Rb3] Remember that the queen is very often misplaced on b3. Black is already better after} Bg4 13. Nc3 Nxd4 14. Qxd5 Qxd5 15. Bxd5 Rfe8 $36 {[%csl Ra1,Ga8,Rc1,Gd4,Ge8,Gg4,Gg7] Symmetrical position, but look at the pieces: only Black can be better.}) 12... Bg4 {[%cal Re2f4] Not the only move, but the easiest one. We do not allow Nf4.} 13. Re1 {[%cal Ge1e2] This is probably White's best try. His idea is to eventually recapture on e2 with the rook.} (13. f3 $2 {Would be a way to unpin the knight, but is' not a good idea because the bishop on g2 is now very bad:} Be6 14. Nf4 Qb6 $15 {[%csl Rd4]}) (13. h3 {Forces the exchange.} Bxe2 14. Qxe2 Nxd4 15. Qd2 {White has two bishops, but he still needs to recapture the missing pawn.} (15. Bxd4 Bxd4 16. Rad1 Qb6 17. Bxd5 Rad8 $11) 15... Nf5 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gf5e3]} 16. Bc5 Re8 17. Qxd5 Qc7 $132 {[%csl Rc5,Gf5,Gg7][%cal Ga8d8] White has two bishops, but our pieces are much more active.}) 13... Re8 $1 {[%cal Ge8e1]} 14. h3 (14. Qd2 Bxe2 15. Rxe2 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Rxe2 17. Qxe2 Bxd4 $11) 14... Bxe2 (14... Bf5 $132 {is also possible, if you want to keep the game more complicated.}) 15. Rxe2 Bxd4 $1 (15... Nxd4 $4 {Be careful because this would be a huge mistake:} 16. Bxd4 Rxe2 17. Bxg7 $18) 16. Bxd4 Rxe2 17. Qxe2 Nxd4 18. Qe5 Nc6 19. Qxd5 Qb6 $11 {White has a good bishop, but there isn't much material left, and our pieces are very fine. This is just a draw.}) 9... d5 {[%csl Rc1] Better to dealy the exchange on d4. Why? Because White will not be able to activate his bishop on c1 for a few more moves.} (9... Nxd4 {In my opinion, it's better for us to don't capture immediately on d4.} 10. exd4 d5 11. cxd5 Nxd5 {White can play now} 12. h4 $5 {[%cal Gc1g5] And he may have Bg5 ideas. Of course, Black's position is still fine objectively, but it could potentially become unpleasant.}) 10. cxd5 (10. Nxc6 $6 {Is a positional mistake.} bxc6 $15 {[%csl Gc6,Gd5,Rg2,Gg7][%cal Yg7a1,Rg2d5] Black is already preferable. Our bishop on g7 is much stronger than White's one on g2. For example:} 11. Qa4 a5 {[%cal Gc8a6] We prepare Ba6.} 12. Rd1 Ba6 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. e4 {Looks critical, but after} d4 $1 {It's difficult for White to equalize:} 15. e5 $1 {only move, otherwise our position will be winning.} Nf5 16. Ne4 (16. Bxa8 $4 Qxa8 $19 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Ga8h1] Black is winning.}) 16... Bxe5 17. Nc5 Ra7 18. Nxa6 Rxa6 $15 {Maybe White can hold, but if somebody is better, then it's for sure Black.}) 10... Nxd5 11. Nxd5 (11. h4 {doesn't make sense now, because after} h5 $11 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Rc1g5] Compared to the 9...Nxd4 variation, White doesn't have Bg5 ideas.}) 11... exd5 {[%cal Yc6d4] Very likely, we will take on d4 one day, reaching a symmetrical and drawish position. But if White is not careful, we might also not take on d4!} 12. Qb3 {You have a choice now:} (12. Nxc6 $6 bxc6 $15 {[%cal Gg7a1] Only Black can be better, thanks to the strong bishop on g7.}) (12. Nb3 $6 a5 $36 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Ga5a4,Ga4a3] White's knight on b3 doesn't stay well.}) 12... a5 $5 $146 {This is a more interesting option if you want to keep the position more complicated.} (12... Nxd4 {is good enough to make a draw:} 13. exd4 {Now, the position is very drawish after both. Black will need to be a bit accurate, but 90% it will be a draw.} Bxd4 $11 (13... Be6 $11)) {White can always decide to exchange everything} 13. Qxd5 (13. Rd1 $6 {Normal move, but a mistake!} a4 14. Qxd5 Bg4 $1 $36) 13... Qxd5 14. Bxd5 Nxd4 15. exd4 Rd8 $11 {But then, compared to the 12...Nxd4 variation: White doesn't even have even a symbolical edge: it's just a draw.} *

