{[%evp 0,34,15,-18,15,13,17,10,10,10,10,-15,-1,-29,-29,-35,9,-17,-19,-19,-27,-25,-17,-43,9,9,16,24,24,24,13,9,17,39,12,12,12]} 1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. e4 {The Botvinnik system is a variation with a very long history. White's idea is to develop with Nge2-00-d3, and then try to play h3-Be3 with d4 ideas, or sometimes f4. Nowadays, it's not so popular anymore. First of all, even if White manges to develop his pieces in a desired way, this doesn't cause any problem to the Black color. Secondly, as we will see, it's very difficult for White to achieve his ideal set-up.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] This is a very strong move. Our idea is to play b7-b5 quickly.} 6. a4 {[%cal Gb7b5,Rb2b4] This is White's best move. However, the inclusion of a6-a4 means that White will never be able to play for b2-b4, while Black can play for b7-b5.} (6. Nge2 {it's White's standard move, but we are ready for the immediate} b5 $1 7. d3 (7. cxb5 $6 {Capturing the pawn is critical but not good:} axb5 8. Nxb5 Ba6 9. Nec3 (9. Nbc3 {Black is better after many moves like Nb4, Bd3, but I like the following option:} h5 $17 {[%cal Gh5h4] We are ready to play h4, and Nb4 ideas are always available. White is seriously worse.}) 9... Bxc3 $1 {We give-up our strong bishop for concrete reasons.} 10. Nxc3 Nb4 {[%cal Gb4d3]} 11. Bf1 {only move.} Bd3 $1 12. Bxd3 Nxd3+ 13. Kf1 Qc8 $36 {[%csl Gd3,Rf1][%cal Gf7f5,Gc5c4] We have a wonderful initiative. We can continue with c4 or with f5, and White's king is weak, while our knight on d3 is a beast.}) 7... Rb8 $1 {It's very important to play this useful move before pushing b5-b4.} (7... b4 $6 {This move is not good for concrete reasons:} 8. Na4 $1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ga4c5] White attacks our c5 pawn.} d6 (8... Qa5 {doesn't help us because of} 9. Be3 $16) 9. e5 $1 $36 {And White can fight for the advantage.}) 8. O-O (8. cxb5 axb5 9. a3 {Is the best, according to the engine, but Black is still preferable after} b4 10. axb4 cxb4 11. Nd5 e6 12. Ne3 Nge7 $132 {[%csl Yg7][%cal Ge8g8,Gd7d5,Yg7a1] We can continue with 00-d5, the material is equal, but we have more space, and our bishop g7 is very strong.}) 8... b4 9. Nd5 (9. Na4 $6 {now this is not good} d6 $15 {[%csl Ra4] White's knight on a4 is misplaced, and White cannot justify it by playing e5, like we have seen in the 7...b4 variation.}) 9... e6 10. Ne3 Nge7 11. f4 {This is not necessarily the best, but f5 is almost always a good response to White's f2-f4. The position is balanced, but from a practical point of view, it's much easier to play it with Black.} f5 $5 $132) (6. d3 b5 7. Nge2 {transposes in 6.Nge2.}) 6... d6 7. d3 {Now, Black has a choice: we can develop the knight on f6 or on e7. I prefer it on e7, but objectively, both moves are fine.} (7. Nge2 {is a less precise move order.} h5 $5 {This is an interesting extra option.} ({We can just transpose in 7.d3 after} 7... e6 8. d3) 8. h3 (8. O-O $2 h4 $17) 8... g5 $5 $146 {my new idea.} 9. d3 g4 10. hxg4 Bxg4 $132 {The position is complicated, but the engine slightly prefers Black. You are not forced to go for it, because you can always play 7...e6 transposing in the mainline, but agree with me that it's not wise for White to allow this extra option.}) 7... e6 {This is my recommendation. I prefer to have the knight on e7 for two reasons: our bishop g7 will still have a strong influence on the diagonal, and we will always have the option to play f7-f5. I repeat myself: I don't want to say that e6-Nge7 is better than Nf6; this is just my personal preference.} (7... Nf6 {this is another very sound way to develop, for example:} 8. Nge2 O-O 9. O-O Rb8 10. h3 Ne8 $132 {[%cal Ge8c7,Gb7b5] We play for Nc7-b5.}) 8. Nge2 Nge7 9. O-O O-O 10. Rb1 {[%csl Gb1][%cal Yc1e3,Yc6d4,Gb2b4] This is a standard-useful move for White. The idea is to continue with Be3, and when we will play Nd4, White will have b2-b4 ideas.} ({Whenever White plays} 10. f4 {we can at least play} f5 $132) ({Whenever White plays} 10. Be3 {[%cal Gd3d4] with the idea d4, we can block it by playing} Nd4 $132) 10... Bd7 $1 {The most precise continuation, in my opinion.} (10... Rb8 $6 {Is not so accurate because it allows White to execute his idea:} 11. Be3 Nd4 12. b4 $1 $14) 11. Be3 Qa5 $1 {This is a strong prophylactic move against d4.} (11... Nd4 $6 12. b4 $14) 12. d4 {White's idea.} ({if White plays a waiting move like} 12. h3 {then we can already play} Nd4 $132 {[%csl Ga5][%cal Ge7c6,Rb2b4,Ya5b4] Because White doesn't have the b2-b4 idea. Our plan will be to play Nec6 next, and then we can retreat the queen to a more standard square like c7.}) 12... cxd4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 {the simplest solution} (13... Ne5 {is also very strong, but more concrete.}) 14. Bxd4 Bxa4 $1 {key move.} 15. Nxa4 Bxd4 16. Qxd4 Qxa4 17. Qxd6 Nc6 $11 {[%csl Gc6,Rg2] Objectively, our position is absolutely fine, but in practice, it might be even easier to play it from the Black's side because White's bishop on g2 could be less strong than our knight.} *

