{[%evp 0,42,27,-20,16,16,13,7,10,0,1,-4,-4,-13,-5,-14,-5,-15,-6,-1,-17,-18,8,-3,85,47,7,9,14,10,10,14,10,-25,-36,-26,-18,-26,-35,-44,-10,-22,-1,-15,-3]} 1. c4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 {Useful waiting move for White, they wait to see our development. I don't think it is a try for an advantage, but it's a try to get a playable game.} Nf6 {[%csl Gd7,Ge7] I prefer this move, because we still keep the pawn structure flexible.} (5... e6 {is possible, but not my recommendation, because White can play} 6. h4 $5 {A lot of games here, Kramnik played it many times.} Nf6 {is the strongest according to the engine.} (6... h6 {is Black's usual response, but maybe this is already something for White.} 7. h5 g5 8. Bxc6 $5 {Strange move, but can be something.} dxc6 9. f4 $13 {Fedoseev-Raja, 2022.}) 7. Nh3 {is White's idea. What to do now?} O-O {is too early.} 8. Bg5 (8. h5 $5 $146 {Even this can be an idea.} Nxh5 9. Bg5 $13 {[%eval 0,0] according to engine, but very complicated game.}) 8... h6 9. Bd2 $13 {[%csl Rh6] Of course, Black's position is fine, but maybe you can end up in some preparation.}) 6. e4 {White plays a Botvinnik, where the knight is on f6. We analyzed a different type(with the knight on e7), but it doesn't matter that White tricked us, the Botvinnik is not dangerous.} (6. Bf4 $5 {[%cal Gf4b8] was played in a very nice game by GM Eljanov. The idea is the same as 6.Bd2, but this time, it stops Rb8.} d6 {To make the bishop on d6 not great.} 7. Qc1 {[%cal Gf4h6] is the idea.} (7. Nf3 {White can also play without the Qc1 plan, but what is the bishop doing on f4? You can play any move.} O-O $11) 7... h6 {is my recommendation. Black covers the g5 square, as well as the h6 one.} (7... h5 $146 {is also possible here, why not?} 8. Nf3 b6 $132 {[%cal Gc8b7] There is no tactic on the diagonal.} (8... Qd7 {You can also start with this move.})) 8. Rb1 {Eljanov-Hansen, Reykjavik 2015.} (8. Nf3 Be6 $11 {[%cal Gd8d7,Gd6d5] Very easy position for Black.}) 8... Be6 9. Nf3 Qd7 (9... d5 {is met with} 10. Ne5 $1 $36 {This was White's idea.}) 10. h3 {[%csl Rc1,Gd7,Ge6,Rf4] I think Black's pieces are better placed, for exmaple:} (10. O-O {If castle, we can use White's idea!} Bh3 $1 $11) 10... a6 11. a3 Rb8 12. b4 {Both sides can achieve b4 or b5.} cxb4 13. axb4 b5 14. cxb5 axb5 $11 {[%cal Gf6d5] Probably equal, but Black has the more pleasant game.}) (6. Bd2 {White's idea is Qc1-Bh6.} Rb8 7. Qc1 h5 $5 {I suggest to stop Bh6.} (7... a6 {allows White's idea.} 8. Bh6 $13 {It might be something for White.}) 8. Nf3 a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] We play with b5 next.} 9. O-O d6 {or you can play just with d6.} (9... b5 $132 {Very interesting new position.}) 10. a4 b6 $11 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ge8g8] Position is fine for Black, for example:} 11. Rb1 Bb7 12. Bg5 Qd7 {It's easier to find useful moves for Black, than for White.} 13. Qd2 O-O {You can also delay it, but this is fine.} 14. Bh6 Nd4 {All bishops will most likely get exchanged.} 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 $15 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Gb7g2] According to the engine, Black is slightly better.}) (6. Be3 $6 {I don't undesrtand White's idea.} b6 $15 {Just slightly better for Black.}) (6. Bg5 {Strange play, seen in the game Rozen-Papadiamandis, 2024.} h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 8. Qd2 {We can't castle yet, but after} Bg7 $11 {At least no problem for Black.}) (6. b3 $2 {White would like to develop the bishop on the long diagonal, but this runs into:} Ne4 $1 $17 {[%cal Gg7a1] And we win material.}) (6. Qd2 {White defends the knight first, so the plan is b3,} O-O 7. b3 {is White's idea, now Black should play for d7-d5.} (7. h4 $6 {is not scary now, because there is a queen on d2, not a bishop.} e6 $36 {[%cal Gd7d5] Black has some initiative already.}) 7... e6 8. Bxc6 $1 {White's best. The position is very strange.} (8. Bb2 $6 {Sadwhani-Gukesh, 2023.} d5 $1 $17 {Black has already a serious advantage, because we have the center and White's pieces are misplaced.}) 8... dxc6 {is my offer.} 9. Nf3 {So White plays for the structure, but light squares.} Nh5 $15 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gf6f5,Ge6e5] -0.20 for engine, so 6.Qd2 is not a great move either.}) (6. e3 {[%csl Gd3,Gf6] It's almost a Fischer system, but our knight is on f6. However, White lost a tempo on d3.} O-O 7. Nge2 e6 8. O-O d5 {[%cal Gd5d4] Very good position, probably White needs to take.} 9. cxd5 exd5 {Why not with the pawn?} 10. d4 cxd4 11. exd4 {Symmetrical position, White's knight can go to f4, but it's Black to move.} Re8 {[%cal Re2f4,Gc8g4] and Nf4 is not so easy to achieve.} 12. h3 Ne4 $1 $11 {Probably White has equality, but not more for sure.}) (6. Nh3 {White's idea to put the knight on f4.} O-O 7. Nf4 d6 8. O-O {White can play this move, but after} (8. h4 $6 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Rc1h6] I don't think h4 is a good move, because no Bh6 ideas with the knight on f4.} Bg4 {To play f3 looks very strange.} 9. h5 Nxh5 10. Nxh5 Bxh5 {This is the game MVL-Wei Yi.} 11. f3 f5 12. Nd5 {Here Wei Yi played a very strange e5 move, but it was a blitz game.} e6 $5 {is a stronger move.} 13. Nf4 {looks scary, but} Qe8 {Black just defends material.} 14. Nxh5 gxh5 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gg7f6,Gh5h4] Bad structure, but advantage for Black, of course.} 15. f4 {Now the bishop on c1 is doomed.} Bf6 16. Bf3 h4 17. gxh4 Nd4 $17) 8... Rb8 $36 {[%csl Ga7,Rf4][%cal Ga7a6,Gc8d7,Gb7b5] The knight on f4 is not fantastic, because d5 is not an outpost, Black has easy play.}) (6. a3 {Transposes to the a3 line, we have already analyzed.}) 6... a6 {The usual queenside plan.} 7. Nge2 {I believe it's better to always start with 7.a4, because you never know if b5 works.} O-O (7... b5 $2 {But right now it doesn't, because of} 8. e5 $1 $16 {Typical idea.}) 8. O-O Rb8 {Now b5 is a threat.} 9. a4 d6 {So now White's plan is to provide d3-d4, but as you will see it is not so easy.} 10. h3 {That's why White usually start with this.} (10. Rb1 $5 {can be an interesting try.} Bg4 $5 {But we get the opportunity to play this move.} (10... Ne8 $6 11. Be3 {[%csl Gb1] And the point is that White saved a half-tempo on h3. Rb1 is more useful.} Nc7 12. d4 $14) 11. f3 {has to be played, but of course, it's not the same after} (11. h3 {If h3 now, we are very happy to play} Bxe2 12. Nxe2 (12. Qxe2 Nd4 $15 {[%cal Gb7b5]}) 12... b5 $36 {d4 is under control.}) 11... Bd7 {[%csl Rg2] White's bishop on g2 is closed.} 12. Be3 Ne8 13. d4 {White plays the desired break, but not enough for an advantage.} cxd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 {Maroczy, but the pawn on f3 is not the same.} b5 $5 {is probably the easiest.} 16. axb5 axb5 17. cxb5 Nc7 {Absolutely fine position, for example:} 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Qd4+ Kg8 20. b4 Nxb5 21. Nxb5 Bxb5 $11 {[%csl Rg1,Rg2] It's even -0.10 for Black. The bishop and king are potentially vulnerable thanks to the f3 move.}) (10. Be3 $6 {runs into} Ng4 $1 $15) 10... Ne8 11. Be3 {And now it's an important moment, because out of 1000 games, the majority of players commited a mistake:} b5 $1 {The best solution, and it just kills the game.} (11... Nc7 $6 {The most played move, but after} 12. d4 $1 {White is slightly better.} cxd4 13. Nxd4 Ne6 14. Nde2 $14 {[%csl Re6] The knight on e6 is very strange in a Maroczy.}) (11... Nd4 {was also tried, the 2nd most common move, but White can play} 12. Rb1 $13 {[%cal Gb2b4] With the idea of b4, and the position is not so clear.}) 12. axb5 axb5 13. Nxb5 {If White takes the pawn, both options are good.} Nc7 $1 {More precise.} (13... Bxb2 $11 {Symmetrical structure, no problem.}) 14. Nec3 (14. Nxc7 Qxc7 $36 {The b2 pawn is undefendable.}) 14... Nxb5 15. Nxb5 {The best recapture.} (15. cxb5 $6 {White can't hold on to material.} Nd4 $15 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gd8b6] Alreadly slightly better.}) 15... Bxb2 {The position is just equal, for example:} 16. Bh6 Bxa1 17. Qxa1 f6 18. Bxf8 Qxf8 {is maybe easier, to avoid f4.} (18... Kxf8 {If I were to choose one side, it is probably Black, but of course, it is still a new complicated position.} 19. f4 Bb7 20. e5 dxe5 21. fxe5 f5 $13 {But Black is not worse for sure.}) 19. d4 {White achieves d4, but it's maximum for equality.} cxd4 20. Nxd4 Nxd4 21. Qxd4 Be6 $11 {Just equal position.} *

